qText: Hamidullah, Hamidullah! am I late?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Do not apologize,
speaker: Hamidullah

qText: You are always late.
speaker: Hamidullah

qText:
Kindly answer my question. Am I late? Has Mahmoud Ali eaten all
the food? If so I go elsewhere. Mr. Mahmoud Ali, how are you?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Thank you, Dr. Aziz, I am dying.
speaker: Mahmoud Ali

qText: Dying before your dinner? Oh, poor Mahmoud Ali!
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Hamidullah here is actually dead. He passed away just as you rode
up on your bike.
speaker: Mahmoud Ali

qText: Yes, that is so,
speaker: Hamidullah

qText:
Imagine us both as addressing
you from another and a happier world.
speaker: Hamidullah

qText:
Does there happen to be such a thing as a hookah in that happier
world of yours?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Aziz, don't chatter. We are having a very sad talk.
speaker: Hamidullah

qText: Well, look at my own experience this morning.
speaker: Mahmoud Ali

qText: I only contend that it is possible in England,
speaker: Hamidullah

qText:
It is impossible here. Aziz! The red-nosed boy has again insulted
me in Court. I do not blame him. He was told that he ought to
insult me. Until lately he was quite a nice boy, but the others
have got hold of him.
speaker: Mahmoud Ali
menEnts: [[['Dr. Aziz'], ['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Ronny Heaslop']]]

qText:
Yes, they have no chance here, that is my point. They come out
intending to be gentlemen, and are told it will not do. Look at
Lesley, look at Blakiston, now it is your red-nosed boy, and
Fielding will go next. Why, I remember when Turton came out first.
It was in another part of the Province. You fellows will not
believe me, but I have driven with Turton in his carriage   Turton!
Oh yes, we were once quite intimate. He has shown me his stamp
collection.
speaker: Hamidullah
menEnts: [[['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Mahmoud Ali', 'Dr. Aziz'], ['Mr. Turton'], ['Mr. Turton'], ['Mr. Turton'], ['Hamidullah', 'Mr. Turton'], ['Mr. Turton'], ['Mr. Turton']]]

qText:
He would expect you to steal it now. Turton! But red-nosed boy
will be far worse than Turton!
speaker: Mahmoud Ali

qText:
I do not think so. They all become exactly the same, not worse,
not better. I give any Englishman two years, be he Turton or
Burton. It is only the difference of a letter. And I give any
Englishwoman six months. All are exactly alike. Do you not agree
with me?
speaker: Hamidullah

qText: I do not,
speaker: Mahmoud Ali

qText:
For
my own part I find such profound differences among our rulers.
Red-nose mumbles, Turton talks distinctly, Mrs. Turton takes
bribes, Mrs. Red-nose does not and cannot, because so far there is
no Mrs. Red-nose.
speaker: Mahmoud Ali

qText: Bribes?
speaker: Hamidullah

qText:
Did you not know that when they were lent to Central India over
a Canal Scheme, some Rajah or other gave her a sewing machine in
solid gold so that the water should run through his state.
speaker: Mahmoud Ali

qText: And does it?
speaker: Hamidullah

qText:
No, that is where Mrs. Turton is so skilful. When we poor blacks
take bribes, we perform what we are bribed to perform, and the law
discovers us in consequence. The English take and do nothing. I
admire them.
speaker: Mahmoud Ali

qText: We all admire them. Aziz, please pass me the hookah.
speaker: Hamidullah

qText: Oh, not yet   hookah is so jolly now.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: You are a very selfish boy.
speaker: Hamidullah

qText:
But take my case   the case of young Hugh Bannister. Here is the
son of my dear, my dead friends, the Reverend and Mrs. Bannister,
whose goodness to me in England I shall never forget or describe.
They were father and mother to me, I talked to them as I do now.
In the vacations their Rectory became my home. They entrusted all
their children to me   I often carried little Hugh about   I took him
up to the Funeral of Queen Victoria, and held him in my arms above
the crowd.
speaker: Hamidullah

qText: Queen Victoria was different,
speaker: Mahmoud Ali

qText:
I learn now that this boy is in business as a leather merchant at
Cawnpore. Imagine how I long to see him and to pay his fare that
this house may be his home. But it is useless. The other
Anglo-Indians will have got hold of him long ago. He will probably
think that I want something, and I cannot face that from the son
of my old friends. Oh, what in this country has gone wrong with
everything, Vakil Sahib? I ask you.
speaker: Hamidullah

qText:
Why talk about the English? Brrrr . . . ! Why be
either friends with the fellows or not friends? Let us shut them
out and be jolly. Queen Victoria and Mrs. Bannister were the only
exceptions, and they're dead.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: No, no, I do not admit that, I have met others.
speaker: Hamidullah

qText: So have I,
speaker: Mahmoud Ali

qText:
All ladies
are far from alike.
speaker: Mahmoud Ali

qText: She said
speaker: _unknowable

qText:
in
the most natural way.
speaker: _unknowable

qText:
She offered me a lozenge when the dust
irritated my throat.
speaker: _unknowable

qText:
But of course all this is
exceptional. The exception does not prove the rule. The average
woman is like Mrs. Turton, and, Aziz, you know what she is.
speaker: Mahmoud Ali

qText:
Come and see my wife a little
then,
speaker: Hamidullah

qText: Once is enough.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Yes, he has done his duty,
speaker: Hamidullah

qText:
Do not tease him
so. He carries on his family, two boys and their sister.
speaker: Hamidullah

qText:
Aunt, they live most comfortably with my wife's mother, where she
was living when she died. I can see them whenever I like. They are
such very, very small children.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
And he sends them the whole of his salary and lives like a
low-grade clerk, and tells no one the reason. What more do you
require him to do?
speaker: Hamidullah

qText:
What is to become of all our daughters if men refuse
to marry? They will marry beneath them, or
speaker: Hamidullah Begum

qText:
Perhaps
. . . but later . . .
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: You mustn't put off what you think right,
speaker: Hamidullah

qText:
That
is why India is in such a plight, because we put off things.
speaker: Hamidullah

qText: Old Callendar wants to see me at his bungalow,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: He might have the politeness to say why.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Some case, I daresay.
speaker: Hamidullah

qText:
I daresay not, I daresay nothing. He has found out our dinner
hour, that's all, and chooses to interrupt us every time, in order
to show his power.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Major Callendar'], ['Mahmoud Ali', 'Hamidullah', 'Dr. Aziz'], ['Mahmoud Ali', 'Hamidullah', 'Dr. Aziz'], ['Major Callendar']]]

qText:
On the one hand he always does this, on the other it may be a
serious case, and you cannot know,
speaker: Hamidullah

qText:
Had you not better clean your
teeth after pan?
speaker: Hamidullah

qText:
If my teeth are to be cleaned, I don't go at all. I am an Indian,
it is an Indian habit to take pan. The Civil Surgeon must put up
with it. Mohammed Latif, my bike, please.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Aziz, Aziz, imprudent boy. . . .
speaker: Hamidullah

qText: But the sahib has left me some message?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: No.
speaker: The Servant

qText: Mrs. Lesley, it _is_ a tonga,
speaker: Mrs. Callendar

qText: Ours?
speaker: Mrs. Lesley

qText: Take the gifts the gods provide, anyhow,
speaker: Mrs. Lesley

qText: O Tonga wallah, club, club. Why doesn't the fool go?
speaker: _unknowable

qText: Go, I will pay you to-morrow,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: You are most welcome, ladies.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Saying nothing?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Then I will write him a letter.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Tell him I have called, that is
sufficient,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Here is my card.
Call me a tonga.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Huzoor, all are at the club.
speaker: The Servant

qText: Then telephone for one down to the railway station.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Enough, enough, I prefer to
walk.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Madam!
Madam! Madam!
speaker: Dr. Aziz
refExp: he was furiously angry and shouted

qText: Oh! Oh!
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
Madam, this is a mosque, you have no right here at all; you should
have taken off your shoes; this is a holy place for Moslems.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I have taken them off.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: You have?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I left them at the entrance.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Then I ask your pardon.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I am truly sorry for speaking.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Yes, I was right, was I not? If I remove my shoes, I am allowed?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
Of course, but so few ladies take the trouble, especially if
thinking no one is there to see.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: That makes no difference. God is here.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Madam!
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Please let me go.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Oh, can I do you some service now or at any time?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: No, thank you, really none   good night.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: May I know your name?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Mrs. Moore.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Mrs.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Mrs. Moore, I am afraid I startled you. I shall tell my
community   our friends   about you. That God is here   very good, very
fine indeed. I think you are newly arrived in India.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Yes   how did you know?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: By the way you address me. No, but can I call you a carriage?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
I have only come from the club. They are doing a play that I have
seen in London, and it was so hot.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: What was the name of the play?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Cousin Kate.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
I think you ought not to walk at night alone, Mrs. Moore. There
are bad characters about and leopards may come across from the
Marabar Hills. Snakes also.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: For example, a six-spot beetle,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
You pick it up,
it bites, you die.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: But you walk about yourself.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Oh, I am used to it.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Used to snakes?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: I'm a doctor,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Snakes don't dare bite
me.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Please may I ask you a question now? Why do
you come to India at this time of year, just as the cold weather
is ending?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I intended to start earlier, but there was an unavoidable delay.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
It will soon be so unhealthy for you! And why ever do you come to
Chandrapore?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: To visit my son. He is the City Magistrate here.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
Oh no, excuse me, that is quite impossible. Our City Magistrate's
name is Mr. Heaslop. I know him intimately.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: He's my son all the same,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: But, Mrs. Moore, how can he be?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I was married twice.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Yes, now I see, and your first husband died.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: He did, and so did my second husband.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Then we are in the same box,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Then is the
City Magistrate the entire of your family now?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: No, there are the younger ones   Ralph and Stella in England.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: And the gentleman here, is he Ralph and Stella's half-brother?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Quite right.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
Mrs. Moore, this is all extremely strange, because like yourself
I have also two sons and a daughter. Is not this the same box with
a vengeance?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: What are their names? Not also Ronny, Ralph, and Stella, surely?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
No, indeed. How funny it sounds!
Their names are quite different and will surprise you. Listen,
please. I am about to tell you my children's names. The first is
called Ahmed, the second is called Karim, the third   she is the
eldest   Jamila. Three children are enough. Do not you agree with
me?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I do.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Would you care to see over the Minto Hospital one morning?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I have nothing else to offer at Chandrapore.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Thank you, I have seen it already, or I should have liked to come
with you very much.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: I suppose the Civil Surgeon took you.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Yes, and Mrs. Callendar.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Ah! A very charming lady.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Possibly, when one knows her better.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: What? What? You didn't like her?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
She was certainly intending to be kind, but I did not find her
exactly charming.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
She has just taken my tonga without my
permission   do you call that being charming?   and Major Callendar
interrupts me night after night from where I am dining with my
friends and I go at once, breaking up a most pleasant entertainment,
and he is not there and not even a message. Is this charming, pray?
But what does it matter? I can do nothing and he knows it. I am
just a subordinate, my time is of no value, the verandah is good
enough for an Indian, yes, yes, let him stand, and Mrs. Callendar
takes my carriage and cuts me dead . . .
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Mrs. Callendar'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Major Callendar'], ['Mahmoud Ali', 'Hamidullah', 'Dr. Aziz'], ['Major Callendar'], ['Major Callendar'], ['Major Callendar'], ['Mrs. Callendar']]]

qText:
You understand me, you know what others feel. Oh, if others
resembled you!
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
I don't think I understand people
very well. I only know whether I like or dislike them.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Then you are an Oriental.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Indians are not allowed into the Chandrapore Club even as guests,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
I want to see
the _real_ India,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
I want to see it too, and I only wish we could. Apparently the
Turtons will arrange something for next Tuesday.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
It'll end in an elephant ride, it always does. Look at this
evening. _Cousin Kate!_ Imagine, _Cousin Kate!_ But where have you
been off to? Did you succeed in catching the moon in the Ganges?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: I went to the mosque, but I did not catch the moon.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: The angle would have altered   she rises later.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Later and later,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
Let me think   we don't see the other side of the moon out here,
no.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Come, India's not as bad as all that,
speaker: _unknowable

qText:
Other side of the earth, if you like, but we stick to the same
old moon.
speaker: _unknowable

qText:
We aren't even seeing the other side of the world; that's our
complaint,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Have a drink,
speaker: Mr. Turton

qText:
Mrs. Moore   Miss
Quested   have a drink, have two drinks.
speaker: Mr. Turton

qText:
The long and the short of it is Heaslop's
a sahib; he's the type we want, he's one of us,
speaker: Mr. Turton

qText:
Hear,
hear!
speaker: _unknowable
refExp: another civilian who was leaning over the billiard table said

qText: Adela, have a drink; mother, a drink.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
addressee: ['Mrs. Callendar', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText:
Fielding! how's one to see the
real India?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
addressee: ['Cyril Fielding', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Mrs. Callendar', 'Mrs. Moore']
refExp: he called out to another passerby

qText: Try seeing Indians,
speaker: Cyril Fielding
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Callendar', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText: Who was that?
speaker: _unknowable
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Callendar', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText: Our schoolmaster   Government College.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
addressee: ['Mrs. Callendar', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText: As if one could avoid seeing them,
speaker: Mrs. Lesley
addressee: ['Mrs. Callendar', 'Adela Quested', 'Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText: I've avoided,
speaker: Adela Quested
addressee: ['Mrs. Callendar', 'Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText:
Excepting my own servant, I've
scarcely spoken to an Indian since landing.
speaker: Adela Quested
addressee: ['Mrs. Callendar', 'Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText: Oh, lucky you.
speaker: Mrs. Lesley
addressee: ['Mrs. Callendar', 'Adela Quested', 'Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText: But I want to see them.
speaker: Adela Quested
addressee: ['Mrs. Callendar', 'Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText: Wanting to see Indians! How new that sounds!
speaker: _unknowable
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Callendar', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText:
Natives!
why, fancy!
speaker: _unknowable
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Callendar', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText:
Let me explain. Natives
don't respect one any the more after meeting one, you see.
speaker: The Lady Who Had Been A Nurse
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Callendar', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText: That occurs after so many meetings.
speaker: Adela Quested
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Mrs. Callendar', 'The Lady Who Had Been A Nurse', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText:
What I mean
is, I was a nurse before my marriage, and came across them a great
deal, so I know. I really do know the truth about Indians. A most
unsuitable position for any Englishwoman   I was a nurse in a Native
State. One's only hope was to hold sternly aloof.
speaker: The Lady Who Had Been A Nurse
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Callendar', 'Mrs. Moore']
refExp: the lady entirely stupid and friendly continued

qText: Even from one's patients?
speaker: Adela Quested
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Mrs. Callendar', 'The Lady Who Had Been A Nurse', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText: Why, the kindest thing one can do to a native is to let him die,
speaker: Mrs. Callendar
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'The Lady Who Had Been A Nurse', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText: How if he went to heaven?
speaker: Mrs. Moore
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Callendar', 'The Lady Who Had Been A Nurse']

qText:
He can go where he likes as long as he doesn't come near me. They
give me the creeps.
speaker: Mrs. Callendar
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'The Lady Who Had Been A Nurse', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText:
As a matter of fact I have thought what you were saying about
heaven, and that is why I am against Missionaries,
speaker: The Lady Who Had Been A Nurse
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Callendar', 'Mrs. Moore']
refExp: said the lady who had been a nurse

qText:
I am all for Chaplains, but all against
Missionaries. Let me explain.
speaker: The Lady Who Had Been A Nurse
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Callendar', 'Mrs. Moore']
refExp: said the lady who had been a nurse

qText:
Do you really want to meet the Aryan Brother, Miss Quested? That
can be easily fixed up. I didn't realize he'd amuse you.
speaker: Mr. Turton
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Callendar', 'The Lady Who Had Been A Nurse', 'Mrs. Moore']
menEnts: [[['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested']], [['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Cyril Fielding']]]

qText:
You can practically see any type you like. Take
your choice. I know the Government people and the landowners,
Heaslop here can get hold of the barrister crew, while if you want
to specialize on education, we can come down on Fielding.
speaker: Mr. Turton
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Callendar', 'The Lady Who Had Been A Nurse', 'Mrs. Moore']
menEnts: [[['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested']], [['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Cyril Fielding']]]

qText:
I'm tired of seeing picturesque figures pass before me as a
frieze,
speaker: Adela Quested
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Mrs. Callendar', 'The Lady Who Had Been A Nurse', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText:
It was wonderful when we landed, but
that superficial glamour soon goes.
speaker: Adela Quested
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Mrs. Callendar', 'The Lady Who Had Been A Nurse', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText:
I only want those Indians whom you come across socially   as your
friends.
speaker: Adela Quested
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Mrs. Callendar', 'The Lady Who Had Been A Nurse', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText: Well, we don't come across them socially,
speaker: Mr. Turton
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Mrs. Callendar', 'The Lady Who Had Been A Nurse', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText:
They're full of all the virtues, but we don't, and it's now
eleven-thirty, and too late to go into the reasons.
speaker: Mr. Turton
addressee: ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Mrs. Turton', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Lesley', 'Mrs. Callendar', 'The Lady Who Had Been A Nurse', 'Mrs. Moore']

qText: Miss Quested, what a name!
speaker: Mrs. Turton
refExp: remarked Mrs Turton to her husband

qText:
India does wonders for the judgment, especially during the hot
weather; it has even done wonders for Fielding.
speaker: Mr. Turton

qText: It's decent of the Burra Sahib,
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
Do you know
he's never given a Bridge Party before? Coming on top of the dinner
too! I wish I could have arranged something myself, but when you
know the natives better you'll realize it's easier for the Burra
Sahib than for me. They know him   they know he can't be fooled   I'm
still fresh comparatively. No one can even begin to think of
knowing this country until he has been in it twenty years.   Hullo,
the mater! Here's your cloak.   Well: for an example of the mistakes
one makes. Soon after I came out I asked one of the Pleaders to
have a smoke with me   only a cigarette, mind. I found afterwards
that he had sent touts all over the bazaar to announce the fact   told
all the litigants,
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
menEnts: [[['Adela Quested'], ['Mr. Turton'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Mr. Turton'], ['Mr. Turton'], ['Mr. Turton']], []]

qText:
Ever since then I've dropped
on him in Court as hard as I could. It's taught me a lesson, and
I hope him.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
menEnts: [[['Adela Quested'], ['Mr. Turton'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Mr. Turton'], ['Mr. Turton'], ['Mr. Turton']], []]

qText:
Isn't the lesson that you should invite all the Pleaders to have
a smoke with you?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Perhaps, but time's limited and the flesh weak. I prefer my smoke
at the club amongst my own sort, I'm afraid.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Why not ask the Pleaders to the club?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Not allowed.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
Oh, yes   that's where I got
to   that's where I've been.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Been there when?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Between the acts.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: But, mother, you can't do that sort of thing.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Can't mother?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
No, really not in this country. It's not done. There's the danger
from snakes for one thing. They are apt to lie out in the evening.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Ah yes, so the young man there said.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: This sounds very romantic,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
You meet a young man in a mosque, and then never let me
know!
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
I was going to tell you, Adela, but something changed the
conversation and I forgot. My memory grows deplorable.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Was he nice?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Very nice.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Who was he?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: A doctor. I don't know his name.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
A doctor? I know of no young doctor in Chandrapore. How odd! What
was he like?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
Rather small, with a little moustache and quick eyes. He called
out to me when I was in the dark part of the mosque   about my shoes.
That was how we began talking. He was afraid I had them on, but I
remembered luckily. He told me about his children, and then we
walked back to the club. He knows you well.
speaker: Mrs. Moore
menEnts: [[['Dr. Aziz'], ['Dr. Aziz', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Dr. Aziz', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Ronny Heaslop']]]

qText: I wish you had pointed him out to me. I can't make out who he is.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: He didn't come into the club. He said he wasn't allowed to.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
Oh, good gracious!
Not a Mohammedan? Why ever didn't you tell me you'd been talking
to a native? I was going all wrong.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: A Mohammedan! How perfectly magnificent!
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[], [['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore']]]

qText:
Ronny, isn't that like your mother? While we talk about seeing
the real India, she goes and sees it, and then forgets she's seen
it.
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[], [['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore']]]

qText:
He
called to you in the mosque, did he? How? Impudently? What was he
doing there himself at that time of night?   No, it's not their
prayer time.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
So he called to you over your
shoes. Then it was impudence. It's an old trick. I wish you had
had them on.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: I think it was impudence, but I don't know about a trick,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
His nerves were all on edge   I could tell from his
voice. As soon as I answered he altered.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: You oughtn't to have answered.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Now look here,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
wouldn't you expect a
Mohammedan to answer if you asked him to take off his hat in
church?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: It's different, it's different; you don't understand.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: I know I don't, and I want to. What is the difference, please?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: There's your Ganges.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: It's not much of a dead body that gets down to Chandrapore.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Crocodiles down in it too, how terrible!
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
What a terrible river!
what a wonderful river!
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Aziz! what a charming name!
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: So you and he had a talk. Did you gather he was well disposed?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
Yes, quite,
after the first moment.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
I meant, generally. Did he seem to tolerate us   the brutal
conqueror, the sundried bureaucrat, that sort of thing?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
Oh, yes, I think so, except the Callendars   he doesn't care for
the Callendars at all.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
Oh. So he told you that, did he? The Major will be interested. I
wonder what was the aim of the remark.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Ronny, Ronny! you're never going to pass it on to Major Callendar?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Yes, rather. I must, in fact!
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: But, my dear boy
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
If the Major heard I was disliked by any native subordinate of
mine, I should expect him to pass it on to me.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: But, my dear boy   a private conversation!
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
Nothing's private in India. Aziz knew that when he spoke out, so
don't you worry. He had some motive in what he said. My personal
belief is that the remark wasn't true.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: How not true?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: He abused the Major in order to impress you.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: I don't know what you mean, dear.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
It's the educated native's latest dodge. They used to cringe, but
the younger generation believe in a show of manly independence.
They think it will pay better with the itinerant M.P. But whether
the native swaggers or cringes, there's always something behind
every remark he makes, always something, and if nothing else he's
trying to increase his izzat   in plain Anglo-Saxon, to score. Of
course there are exceptions.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: You never used to judge people like this at home.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: India isn't home,
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
I can't deny that what you say sounds very sensible,
but you really must not hand on to Major Callendar anything I have
told you about Doctor Aziz.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
In return
please don't talk about Aziz to Adela.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Not talk about him? Why?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
There you go again, mother   I really can't explain every thing. I
don't want Adela to be worried, that's the fact; she'll begin
wondering whether we treat the natives properly, and all that sort
of nonsense.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
menEnts: [[['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore']]]

qText:
But she came out to be worried   that's exactly why she's here. She
discussed it all on the boat. We had a long talk when we went on
shore at Aden. She knows you in play, as she put it, but not in
work, and she felt she must come and look round, before she
decided   and before you decided. She is very, very fair-minded.
speaker: Mrs. Moore
menEnts: [[['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Adela Quested']]]

qText: I know,
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Pretty dear,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: It is owing to orders from the L.G.,
speaker: Mahmoud Ali

qText:
Turton would never do this unless compelled. Those high officials
are different   they sympathize, the Viceroy sympathizes, they would
have us treated properly. But they come too seldom and live too
far away. Meanwhile
speaker: Mahmoud Ali

qText: It is easy to sympathize at a distance,
speaker: The Nawab Badahur
refExp: said an old gentleman with a beard

qText:
I value more the kind word that is spoken close to
my ear. Mr. Turton has spoken it, from whatever cause. He speaks,
we hear. I do not see why we need discuss it further.
speaker: The Nawab Badahur
refExp: said an old gentleman with a beard

qText:
We have not all your sweet nature, Nawab Bahadur, nor your
learning.
speaker: Mahmoud Ali
menEnts: [[['The Nawab Badahur'], ['The Nawab Badahur'], ['The Nawab Badahur']]]

qText:
The Lieutenant-Governor may be my very good friend, but I give
him no trouble.
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText:
And all is over. But I can be a
thorn in Mr. Turton's flesh, and if he asks me I accept the
invitation. I shall come in from Dilkusha specially, though I have
to postpone other business.
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText: You will make yourself chip,
speaker: Ram Chand
refExp: suddenly said a little black man

qText: Mr. Ram Chand!
speaker: Mahmoud Ali

qText: Mr. Mahmoud Ali!
speaker: Ram Chand

qText:
Mr. Ram Chand, the Nawab Bahadur can decide what is cheap without
our valuation, I think.
speaker: Mahmoud Ali

qText: I do not expect I shall make myself cheap,
speaker: The Nawab Badahur
refExp: said the Nawab Bahadur to Mr Ram Chand

qText:
I do not see why we should make ourselves
cheap. I do not see why we should. The invitation is worded very
graciously.
speaker: The Nawab Badahur
refExp: said the Nawab Bahadur to Mr Ram Chand

qText:
Till Tuesday, then, gentlemen all, when I hope we
may meet in the flower gardens of the club.
speaker: The Nawab Badahur
refExp: he repeated all that he had said before though at greater length ending up with

qText: It is only just five,
speaker: Mrs. Turton
menEnts: [[], [['Mr. Turton'], ['Mr. Turton'], ['Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton'], ['Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton'], ['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Ronny Heaslop']]]

qText:
My husband will be up
from his office in a moment and start the thing. I have no idea
what we have to do. It's the first time we've ever given a party
like this at the club. Mr. Heaslop, when I'm dead and gone will
you give parties like this? It's enough to make the old type of
Burra Sahib turn in his grave.
speaker: Mrs. Turton
menEnts: [[], [['Mr. Turton'], ['Mr. Turton'], ['Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton'], ['Mrs. Turton', 'Mr. Turton'], ['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Ronny Heaslop']]]

qText:
You wanted something not picturesque
and we've provided it,
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
What do you
think of the Aryan Brother in a topi and spats?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
The great point to remember is that no one who's here matters;
those who matter don't come. Isn't that so, Mrs. Turton?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Absolutely true,
speaker: Mrs. Turton

qText:
The educated Indians
will be no good to us if there's a row, it's simply not worth while
conciliating them, that's why they don't matter. Most of the people
you see are seditious at heart, and the rest 'ld run squealing.
The cultivator   he's another story. The Pathan   he's a man if you
like. But these people   don't imagine they're India.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
the sort of thing no white man could have
written,
speaker: Mrs. Lesley

qText: To work, Mary, to work,
speaker: Mr. Turton

qText:
What do you want me to do? Oh, those
purdah women! I never thought any would come. Oh dear!
speaker: Mrs. Turton

qText: I consider they ought to come over to me.
speaker: Mrs. Turton

qText: Come along, Mary, get it over.
speaker: Mr. Turton

qText:
I refuse to shake hands with any of the men, unless it has to be
the Nawab Bahadur.
speaker: Mrs. Turton

qText: Whom have we so far?
speaker: Mr. Turton

qText:
H'm! h'm! much
as one expected. We know why he's here, I think   over that contract,
and he wants to get the right side of me for Mohurram, and he's
the astrologer who wants to dodge the municipal building regulations,
and he's that Parsi, and he's   Hullo! there he goes   smash into our
hollyhocks. Pulled the left rein when he meant the right. All as
usual.
speaker: Mr. Turton

qText:
They ought never to have been allowed to drive in; it's so bad
for them,
speaker: Mrs. Turton

qText:
Why they come at all I don't know. They hate it as much
as we do. Talk to Mrs. McBryde. Her husband made her give purdah
parties until she struck.
speaker: Mrs. Turton

qText: This isn't a purdah party,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Oh, really,
speaker: Mrs. Turton

qText: Do kindly tell us who these ladies are,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
You're superior to them, anyway. Don't forget that. You're superior
to everyone in India except one or two of the Ranis, and they're
on an equality.
speaker: Mrs. Turton

qText: Is that what you wanted?
speaker: Mrs. Turton

qText:
Please tell these ladies that I wish we could speak their language,
but we have only just come to their country.
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Bhattacharya'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Bhattacharya']]]

qText: Perhaps we speak yours a little,
speaker: _unknowable

qText: Why, fancy, she understands!
speaker: Mrs. Turton

qText: Eastbourne, Piccadilly, High Park Corner,
speaker: _unknowable

qText: Oh yes, they're English-speaking.
speaker: Mrs. Turton

qText: But now we can talk: how delightful!
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: She knows Paris also,
speaker: Mr. Bhattacharya

qText: They pass Paris on the way, no doubt,
speaker: Mrs. Turton

qText: The shorter lady, she is my wife, she is Mrs. Bhattacharya,
speaker: Mr. Bhattacharya

qText:
The taller lady, she is my sister, she is Mrs.
Das.
speaker: Mr. Bhattacharya

qText:
I wonder whether you
would allow us to call on you some day.
speaker: Mrs. Moore
refExp: Mrs Moore had an impulse and said to Mrs Bhattacharya

qText: When?
speaker: Mrs. Bhattacharya

qText: Whenever is convenient.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: All days are convenient.
speaker: Mrs. Bhattacharya

qText: Thursday . . .
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Most certainly.
speaker: Mrs. Bhattacharya

qText:
We shall enjoy it greatly, it would be a real pleasure. What about
the time?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: All hours.
speaker: Mrs. Bhattacharya

qText:
Tell us which you would prefer. We're quite strangers to your
country; we don't know when you have visitors,
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Bhattacharya'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Bhattacharya'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Bhattacharya']]]

qText:
We leave
for Calcutta to-day.
speaker: Mrs. Bhattacharya

qText: Oh, do you?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Oh, but if you do we shall find you gone.
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[['Mr. Bhattacharya', 'Mrs. Bhattacharya'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Mr. Bhattacharya', 'Mrs. Bhattacharya']]]

qText: Yes, yes, you come to us Thursday.
speaker: Mr. Bhattacharya

qText: But you'll be in Calcutta.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: No, no, we shall not.
speaker: Mr. Bhattacharya

qText: We expect you Thursday.
speaker: Mr. Bhattacharya

qText: Thursday . . .
speaker: Mrs. Bhattacharya

qText:
You can't have done such a dreadful thing as to put off going for
our sake?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: No, of course not, we are not such people.
speaker: Mr. Bhattacharya

qText:
I believe that you have. Oh, please   it distresses me beyond
words.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
I'ld like to come very much indeed, and so would Mrs. Moore, I
know.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: I'm rather a hermit, you know.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Much the best thing to be in this place.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Owing to my work and so on, I don't get up much to the club.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
I know, I know, and we never get down from it. I envy you being
with Indians.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Do you care to meet one or two?
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
Very, very much indeed; it's what I long for. This party to-day
makes me so angry and miserable. I think my countrymen out here
must be mad. Fancy inviting guests and not treating them properly!
You and Mr. Turton and perhaps Mr. McBryde are the only people who
showed any common politeness. The rest make me perfectly ashamed,
and it's got worse and worse.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Oh, just what we wanted to hear. And do you know Doctor Aziz?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
I know all about him. I don't know him. Would you like him asked
too?
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Mrs. Moore says he is so nice.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Very well, Miss Quested. Will Thursday suit you?
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
Indeed it will, and that morning we go to this Indian lady's. All
the nice things are coming Thursday.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
I won't ask the City Magistrate to bring you. I know he'll be busy
at that time.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Yes, Ronny is always hard-worked,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
I should
never get like that,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
If one couldn't see the laughable side of these people one
'ld be done for,
speaker: Miss Derek

qText:
Oh, Nancy, how topping! Oh,
Nancy, how killing! I wish I could look at things like that.
speaker: Mrs. Mcbryde
refExp: Mrs McBryde it was she who had been the nurse ceased not to exclaim

qText:
Does Adela talk to you
much?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
I'm so driven with work, I don't see her as much
as I hoped, but I hope she finds things comfortable.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
Adela and I talk mostly about India. Dear, since you mention it,
you're quite right   you ought to be more alone with her than you
are.
speaker: Mrs. Moore
menEnts: [[['Adela Quested'], ['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Ronny Heaslop']]]

qText: Yes, perhaps, but then people'ld gossip.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Well, they must gossip sometime! Let them gossip.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
People are so odd out here, and it's not like home   one's always
facing the footlights, as the Burra Sahib said. Take a silly little
example: when Adela went out to the boundary of the club compound,
and Fielding followed her. I saw Mrs. Callendar notice it. They
notice everything, until they're perfectly sure you're their sort.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
I don't think Adela 'll ever be quite their sort   she's much too
individual.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: I know, that's so remarkable about her,
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: I suppose nothing's on her mind,
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Ask her, ask her yourself, my dear boy.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
Probably she's heard tales of the heat, but of course I should
pack her off to the Hills every April   I'm not one to keep a wife
grilling in the Plains.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Oh, it wouldn't be the weather.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
There's nothing in India but the weather, my dear mother; it's
the Alpha and Omega of the whole affair.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
Yes, as Mr. McBryde was saying, but it's much more the Anglo-Indians
themselves who are likely to get on Adela's nerves. She doesn't
think they behave pleasantly to Indians, you see.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: What did I tell you?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
I
knew it last week. Oh, how like a woman to worry over a side-issue!
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: A side-issue, a side-issue?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: How can it be that?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: We're not out here for the purpose of behaving pleasantly!
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: What do you mean?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
What I say. We're out here to do justice and keep the peace.
Them's my sentiments. India isn't a drawing-room.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Your sentiments are those of a god,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: India likes gods.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: And Englishmen like posing as gods.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
There's no point in all this. Here we are, and we're going to
stop, and the country's got to put up with us, gods or no gods.
Oh, look here,
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
menEnts: [[], [['Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore']]]

qText:
what do you
and Adela want me to do? Go against my class, against all the
people I respect and admire out here? Lose such power as I have
for doing good in this country because my behaviour isn't pleasant?
You neither of you understand what work is, or you 'ld never talk
such eyewash. I hate talking like this, but one must occasionally.
It's morbidly sensitive to go on as Adela and you do. I noticed
you both at the club to-day   after the Burra Sahib had been at all
that trouble to amuse you. I am out here to work, mind, to hold
this wretched country by force. I'm not a missionary or a Labour
Member or a vague sentimental sympathetic literary man. I'm just
a servant of the Government; it's the profession you wanted me to
choose myself, and that's that. We're not pleasant in India, and
we don't intend to be pleasant. We've something more important to
do.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
menEnts: [[], [['Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore']]]

qText: I'm going to argue, and indeed dictate,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: The English are out here to be pleasant.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: How do you make that out, mother?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
Because India is part of the earth. And God has put us on the
earth in order to be pleasant to each other. God . . . is . . .
love.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
God has put us on earth to love our
neighbours and to show it, and He is omnipresent, even in India,
to see how we are succeeding.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
She is
certainly ageing, and I ought not to be vexed with anything she
says.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
The desire to behave pleasantly satisfies God. . . The sincere if
impotent desire wins His blessing. I think every one fails, but
there are so many kinds of failure. Good will and more good will
and more good will. Though I speak with the tongues of . . .
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
I quite see
that. I suppose I ought to get off to my files now, and you'll be
going to bed.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
refExp: He waited until she had done and then said

qText: I suppose so, I suppose so.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
What can you
expect from the fellow?
speaker: Major Callendar

qText:
No grits, no
guts.
speaker: Major Callendar

qText:
Sir, excuse me, I did. I mounted my bike, and it bust in front of
the Cow Hospital. So I had to find a tonga.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Bust in front of the Cow Hospital, did it? And how did you come
to be there?
speaker: Major Callendar

qText: I beg your pardon?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Oh Lord, oh Lord! When I live here
speaker: Major Callendar

qText:
and you
live there   not ten minutes from me   and the Cow Hospital is right
ever so far away the other side of you   _there_   then how did you
come to be passing the Cow Hospital on the way to me? Now do some
work for a change.
speaker: Major Callendar

qText:
I must tell that to Mahmoud Ali,
it'll make him laugh,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Disaster may come,
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText:
but we shall at all events get there safe, even if we do not get
back.
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText:
It will, I think, create a good
impression should two doctors arrive at the same time.
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText:
How unhappy
I am!
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: How unhappy I am!
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Never, never shall I get over this,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Most
certainly my career is a failure, and my sons will be badly brought
up.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Maharajah, salaam,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Send it along
again.
speaker: A Stray Subaltern
refExp: he hit it back to Aziz and called

qText: All right.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Often play?
speaker: A Stray Subaltern

qText: Never.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Let's have another chukker.
speaker: A Stray Subaltern

qText: Oh God!
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Don't you ever fall off?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Plenty.
speaker: A Stray Subaltern

qText: Not you.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
If only they
were all like that,
speaker: _group

qText:
Dr. Aziz, Dr. Aziz, where you been? I waited ten full minutes'
time at your house, then I went.
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText: I am so awfully sorry   I was compelled to go to the Post Office.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Post Office? Do you not send your
servants?
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText: I have so few   my scale is very small.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Your servant spoke to me. I saw your servant.
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText:
But, Dr. Lal, consider. How could I send my servant when you were
coming: you come, we go, my house is left alone, my servant comes
back perhaps, and all my portable property has been carried away
by bad characters in the meantime. Would you have that? The cook
is deaf   I can never count on my cook   and the boy is only a little
boy. Never, never do I and Hassan leave the house at the same time
together. It is my fixed rule.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Dr. Panna Lal'], ['Dr. Panna Lal'], ['Dr. Panna Lal'], ['Dr. Aziz', 'Dr. Panna Lal'], ['Dr. Panna Lal']]]

qText:
Even if this so, what
prevents leaving a chit saying where you go?
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText:
Farther away, or
mine will start out of sympathy,
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText:
It has been so rough and wild this
afternoon. It spoiled some most valuable blossoms in the club
garden, and had to be dragged back by four men. English ladies and
gentlemen looking on, and the Collector Sahib himself taking a
note. But, Dr. Aziz, I'll not take up your valuable time. This will
not interest you, who have so many engagements and telegrams. I am
just a poor old doctor who thought right to pay my respects when
I was asked and where I was asked. Your absence, I may remark, drew
commentaries.
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText: They can damn well comment.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: It is fine to be young. Damn well! Oh, very fine. Damn whom?
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText: I go or not as I please.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Yet you promise me, and then fabricate this tale of a telegram.
Go forward, Dapple.
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText: Please make yourself at home.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
May I really, Mr. Fielding?
It's very good of you,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
I like unconventional
behaviour so extremely.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
The fact is I
have long wanted to meet you,
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Cyril Fielding']], [['Cyril Fielding'], ['The Nawab Badahur']], [['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Dr. Aziz', 'Cyril Fielding']], [['Cyril Fielding'], ['Major Callendar'], ['Major Callendar'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Dr. Aziz', 'Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding']]]

qText:
I have heard so much
about your warm heart from the Nawab Bahadur. But where is one to
meet in a wretched hole like Chandrapore?
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Cyril Fielding']], [['Cyril Fielding'], ['The Nawab Badahur']], [['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Dr. Aziz', 'Cyril Fielding']], [['Cyril Fielding'], ['Major Callendar'], ['Major Callendar'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Dr. Aziz', 'Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding']]]

qText:
When I was greener here, I'll tell you what. I used to wish
you to fall ill so that we could meet that way.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Cyril Fielding']], [['Cyril Fielding'], ['The Nawab Badahur']], [['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Dr. Aziz', 'Cyril Fielding']], [['Cyril Fielding'], ['Major Callendar'], ['Major Callendar'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Dr. Aziz', 'Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding']]]

qText:
I said to myself,
How does Mr. Fielding look this morning? Perhaps pale. And the
Civil Surgeon is pale too, he will not be able to attend upon him
when the shivering commences. I should have been sent for instead.
Then we would have had jolly talks, for you are a celebrated
student of Persian poetry.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Cyril Fielding']], [['Cyril Fielding'], ['The Nawab Badahur']], [['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Dr. Aziz', 'Cyril Fielding']], [['Cyril Fielding'], ['Major Callendar'], ['Major Callendar'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Dr. Aziz', 'Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding']]]

qText: You know me by sight, then.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Of course, of course. You know me?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I know you very well by name.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
I have been here such a short time, and always in the bazaar. No
wonder you have never seen me, and I wonder you know my name. I
say, Mr. Fielding?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Yes?
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
Guess what I look like before you come out. That will be a kind
of game.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: You're five feet nine inches high,
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Jolly good. What next? Have I not a venerable white beard?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Blast!
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Anything wrong?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I've stamped on my last collar stud.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Take mine, take mine.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Have you a spare one?
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Yes, yes, one minute.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Not if you're wearing it yourself.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: No, no, one in my pocket.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Here it is,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Come in with it if you don't mind the unconventionality.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: One minute again.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Many thanks.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
But I always thought that Englishmen kept their rooms so tidy. It
seems that this is not so. I need not be so ashamed.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Everything ranged coldly on
shelves was what _I_ thought.   I say, Mr. Fielding, is the stud
going to go in?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I hae ma doots.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
What's that last sentence, please? Will you teach me some new
words and so improve my English?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Let me put in your stud. I see . . . the shirt back's hole is
rather small and to rip it wider a pity.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Why in hell does one wear collars at all?
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: We wear them to pass the Police.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: What's that?
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
If I'm biking in English dress   starch collar, hat with ditch   they
take no notice. When I wear a fez, they cry,    Your lamp's out!'
Lord Curzon did not consider this when he urged natives of India
to retain their picturesque costumes.   Hooray! Stud's gone
in.   Sometimes I shut my eyes and dream I have splendid clothes
again and am riding into battle behind Alamgir. Mr. Fielding, must
not India have been beautiful then, with the Mogul Empire at its
height and Alamgir reigning at Delhi upon the Peacock Throne?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Two ladies are coming to tea to meet you   I think you know them.
speaker: Cyril Fielding
menEnts: [[['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore']]]

qText: Meet me? I know no ladies.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Not Mrs. Moore and Miss Quested?
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Oh yes   I remember.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
An excessively aged lady;
but will you please repeat the name of her companion?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Miss Quested.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Just as you wish.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
You can talk to Miss Quested about the Peacock Throne if you
like   she's artistic, they say.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Is she a Post Impressionist?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Post Impressionism, indeed! Come along to tea. This world is
getting too much for me altogether.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
I do not
consider Mrs. Moore my friend, I only met her accidentally in my
mosque,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
a single meeting is too short to make a
friend,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Besides the ladies I am expecting one of my assistants   Narayan
Godbole.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Oho, the Deccani Brahman!
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: He wants the past back too, but not precisely Alamgir.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
I should think not. Do you know what Deccani Brahmans say? That
England conquered India from them   from them, mind, and not from
the Moguls. Is not that like their cheek? They have even bribed it
to appear in text-books, for they are so subtle and immensely rich.
Professor Godbole must be quite unlike all other Deccani Brahmans
from all I can hear say. A most sincere chap.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Why don't you fellows run a club in Chandrapore, Aziz?
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
Perhaps   some day . . . just now I see Mrs. Moore and   what's her
name   coming.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I want to ask you something, Dr. Aziz,
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[['Dr. Aziz'], ['Dr. Aziz']], [['Mrs. Moore'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore']]]

qText:
I heard from
Mrs. Moore how helpful you were to her in the mosque, and how
interesting. She learnt more about India in those few minutes' talk
with you than in the three weeks since we landed.
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[['Dr. Aziz'], ['Dr. Aziz']], [['Mrs. Moore'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore']]]

qText:
Oh, please do not mention a little thing like that. Is there
anything else I may tell you about my country?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
I want you to explain a disappointment we had this morning; it
must be some point of Indian etiquette.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: There honestly is none,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
We are by nature a most
informal people.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I am afraid we must have made some blunder and given offence,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: That is even more impossible. But may I know the facts?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
An Indian lady and gentleman were to send their carriage for us
this morning at nine. It has never come. We waited and waited and
waited; we can't think what happened.
speaker: Mrs. Moore
menEnts: [[['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore']]]

qText: Some misunderstanding,
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Oh no, it wasn't that,
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[], [['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore']]]

qText:
They even gave
up going to Calcutta to entertain us. We must have made some stupid
blunder, we both feel sure.
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[], [['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore']]]

qText: I wouldn't worry about that.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Exactly what Mr. Heaslop tells me,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: If one doesn't worry, how's one to understand?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Slack Hindus   they have no idea of society; I know them very well
because of a doctor at the hospital. Such a slack, unpunctual
fellow! It is as well you did not go to their house, for it would
give you a wrong idea of India. Nothing sanitary. I think for my
own part they grew ashamed of their house and that is why they did
not send.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: That's a notion,
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: I do so hate mysteries,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: We English do.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
I dislike them not because I'm English, but from my own personal
point of view,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: I like mysteries but I rather dislike muddles,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: A mystery is a muddle.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Oh, do you think so, Mr. Fielding?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
A mystery is only a high-sounding term for a muddle. No advantage
in stirring it up, in either case. Aziz and I know well that
India's a muddle.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: India's       Oh, what an alarming idea!
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: There'll be no muddle when you come to see me,
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Mrs. Moore']], [['Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Cyril Fielding'], ['Adela Quested', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Mrs. Moore']]]

qText:
Mrs. Moore and everyone   I invite you all   oh,
please.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Mrs. Moore']], [['Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Cyril Fielding'], ['Adela Quested', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Mrs. Moore']]]

qText:
Oh, but we will talk
of something else now,
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Dr. Aziz', 'Adela Quested', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Mrs. Moore']], [['Dr. Aziz', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore']]]

qText:
I wish I lived here. See
this beautiful room! Let us admire it together for a little. See
those curves at the bottom of the arches. What delicacy! It is the
architecture of Question and Answer. Mrs. Moore, you are in India;
I am not joking.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Dr. Aziz', 'Adela Quested', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Mrs. Moore']], [['Dr. Aziz', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore']]]

qText:
I am doing justice here. A poor widow who has been robbed comes
along and I give her fifty rupees, to another a hundred, and so on
and so on. I should like that.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Rupees don't last for ever, I'm afraid,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
Mine would. God would give me more when he saw I gave. Always be
giving, like the Nawab Bahadur. My father was the same, that is
why he died poor.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
So we would sit giving for ever   on a carpet instead of chairs,
that is the chief change between now and then, but I think we would
never punish anyone.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Poor criminal, give him another chance. It only makes a man worse
to go to prison and be corrupted.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: We punish no one, no one,
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[], [['Cyril Fielding'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Cyril Fielding', 'Adela Quested', 'Dr. Aziz', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore']]]

qText:
and in the evening we will give a great banquet with a nautch and
lovely girls shall shine on every side of the tank with fireworks
in their hands, and all shall be feasting and happiness until the
next day, when there shall be justice as before   fifty rupees, a
hundred, a thousand   till peace comes. Ah, why didn't we live in
that time?   But are you admiring Mr. Fielding's house? Do look how
the pillars are painted blue, and the verandah's pavilions   what do
you call them?   that are above us inside are blue also. Look at the
carving on the pavilions. Think of the hours it took. Their little
roofs are curved to imitate bamboo. So pretty   and the bamboos
waving by the tank outside. Mrs. Moore! Mrs. Moore!
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[], [['Cyril Fielding'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Cyril Fielding', 'Adela Quested', 'Dr. Aziz', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore']]]

qText: Well?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
You remember the water by our mosque? It comes down and fills this
tank   a skilful arrangement of the Emperors. They stopped here going
down into Bengal. They loved water. Wherever they went they created
fountains, gardens, hammams. I was telling Mr. Fielding I would
give anything to serve them.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Then back with water
streaming over you and perhaps rather a pain inside. But I did not
mind. All my friends were paining with me. We have a proverb in
Urdu:    What does unhappiness matter when we are all unhappy
together?' which comes in conveniently after mangoes. Miss Quested,
do wait for mangoes. Why not settle altogether in India?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I'm afraid I can't do that,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Visitors like you are too rare.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: They are indeed,
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText:
Such affability is
seldom seen. But what can we offer to detain them?
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText: Mangoes, mangoes.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Even mangoes can be got in England now,
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
They ship them in ice-cold rooms. You can make India in
England apparently, just as you can make England in India.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Frightfully expensive in both cases,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: I suppose so.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: And nasty.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Don't you come too, Adela; you dislike institutions.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Yes, that is so,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: I speak now as a doctor: no.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
But I will send you up a few healthy sweets. I will give myself
that pleasure.
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText: Miss Quested, Professor Godbole's sweets are delicious,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
They will give you a real Indian treat. Ah, in my poor
position I can give you nothing.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
I don't know why you say that, when you have so kindly asked us
to your house.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Yes,
all that is settled,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I invite you all to see me in the Marabar Caves.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I shall be delighted.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Oh, that is a most magnificent entertainment compared to my poor
sweets. But has not Miss Quested visited our caves already?
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText: No. I've not even heard of them.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Not heard of them?
speaker: _group

qText:
The Marabar Caves in the Marabar
Hills?
speaker: _group

qText:
We hear nothing interesting up at the club. Only tennis and
ridiculous gossip.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: I know.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Then tell me everything you will, or I shall never understand
India. Are they the hills I sometimes see in the evening? What are
these caves?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
My dear young sir,
the pot and the kettle! Have you ever heard of that useful proverb?
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText: Are they large caves?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: No, not large.
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText: Do describe them, Professor Godbole.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: It will be a great honour.
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText:
There is an entrance in the rock which you enter,
and through the entrance is the cave.
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText: Something like the caves at Elephanta?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Oh no, not at all; at Elephanta there are sculptures of Siva and
Parvati. There are no sculptures at Marabar.
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText: They are immensely holy, no doubt,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Oh no, oh no.
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText: Still, they are ornamented in some way.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Oh no.
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText:
Well, why are they so famous? We all talk of the famous Marabar
Caves. Perhaps that is our empty brag.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: No, I should not quite say that.
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText: Describe them to this lady, then.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: It will be a great pleasure.
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText: What's happened to Fielding? Where's my mother?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Good evening!
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: I want you and mother at once. There's to be polo.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: I thought there was to be no polo.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Everything's altered. Some soldier men have come in. Come along
and I'll tell you about it.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Your mother will return shortly, sir,
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText:
There is but little to see at our
poor college.
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText:
Come along up and join us, Mr. Heaslop; sit down till your
mother turns up.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
refExp: He had not risen with Godbole and now offensively friendly called

qText: He may not understand that. Allow me
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Don't trouble to come, mother,
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
we're just
starting.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
I say, old man, do excuse me, but I think
perhaps you oughtn't to have left Miss Quested alone.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
refExp: he hurried to Fielding drew him aside and said

qText: I'm sorry, what's up?
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
Well . . . I'm the sun-dried bureaucrat, no doubt; still, I don't
like to see an English girl left smoking with two Indians.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: She stopped, as she smokes, by her own wish, old man.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Yes, that's all right in England.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: I really can't see the harm.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
If you can't see, you can't see. . . . Can't you see that fellow's
a bounder?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: He isn't a bounder,
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
His nerves are on edge,
that's all.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: What should have upset his precious nerves?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: I don't know. He was all right when I left.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Well, it's nothing I've said,
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
I never
even spoke to him.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
Oh well, come along now, and take your ladies away; the catastrophe
over.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
Fielding . . . don't think I'm taking it badly, or anything of
that sort. . . . I suppose you won't come on to the polo with us?
We should all be delighted.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
menEnts: [[['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore']]]

qText:
I'm afraid I can't, thanks all the same. I'm awfully sorry you
feel I've been remiss. I didn't mean to be.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
Good-bye, Mr. Fielding, and thank you so much. . . . What lovely
College buildings!
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Good-bye, Mrs. Moore.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Good-bye, Mr. Fielding. Such an interesting afternoon. . . .
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Good-bye, Miss Quested.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Good-bye, Dr. Aziz.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Good-bye, Mrs. Moore.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Good-bye, Dr. Aziz.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Good-bye, Miss Quested.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
You'll jolly jolly well not forget those
caves, won't you? I'll fix the whole show up in a jiffy.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Thank you. . .
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
What a shame
you leave India so soon! Oh, do reconsider your decision, do stay.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Good-bye, Professor Godbole,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: It's a shame we never heard you sing.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: I may sing now,
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText: Thanks so much: what was that?
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
I will explain in detail. It was a religious song. I placed myself
in the position of a milkmaiden. I say to Shri Krishna,
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText: The god refuses to come. I grow humble and say:
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText:
He refuses to come. This is repeated
several times. The song is composed in a raga appropriate to the
present hour, which is the evening.
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText: But He comes in some other song, I hope?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Oh no, he refuses to come,
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText:
I say to Him, Come, come, come, come,
come, come. He neglects to come.
speaker: Professor Godbole

qText: What was that about caves?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
Mrs. Moore, your delightful doctor has decided on a picnic,
instead of a party in his house; we are to meet him out there   you,
myself, Mr. Fielding, Professor Godbole   exactly the same party.
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[['Mrs. Moore'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Professor Godbole']]]

qText: Out where?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: The Marabar Caves.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Well, I'm blessed,
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
Did he descend to
any details?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
He did not. If you had spoken to him, we could have arranged
them.
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[['Dr. Aziz'], ['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested', 'Dr. Aziz']]]

qText: Have I said anything funny?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
I was only thinking how the worthy doctor's collar climbed up his
neck.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: I thought you were discussing the caves.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
So I am. Aziz was exquisitely dressed, from tie-pin to spats, but
he had forgotten his back collar-stud, and there you have the
Indian all over: inattention to detail; the fundamental slackness
that reveals the race. Similarly, to    meet' in the caves as if they
were the clock at Charing Cross, when they're miles from a station
and each other.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Have you been to them?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: No, but I know all about them, naturally.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Oh naturally!
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Are you too pledged to this expedition, mother?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Mother is pledged to nothing,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
Certainly not to this polo. Will you drive up to the bungalow
first, and drop me there, please? I prefer to rest.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Drop me too,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
I don't want to watch polo either, I'm
sure.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Simpler to drop the polo,
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
menEnts: [[], [['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore']]]

qText:
I
won't have you messing about with Indians any more! If you want to
go to the Marabar Caves, you'll go under British auspices.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
menEnts: [[], [['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore']]]

qText:
I've never heard of these caves, I don't know what or where they
are,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: but I really can't have
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: so much quarrelling and tiresomeness!
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: We must have a thorough talk, Ronny, I'm afraid.
speaker: Adela Quested
refExp: she forced out of herself the undigested remark

qText: My temper's rotten, I must apologize,
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
I didn't
mean to order you and mother about, but of course the way those
Bengalis let you down this morning annoyed me, and I don't want
that sort of thing to keep happening.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: It's nothing to do with them that I . . .
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
No, but Aziz would make some similar muddle over the caves. He
meant nothing by the invitation, I could tell by his voice; it's
just their way of being pleasant.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
It's something very different, nothing to do with caves, that I
wanted to talk over with you.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: I've finally decided we are not going to be married, my dear boy.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
You never said we should marry, my dear girl;
you never bound either yourself or me   don't let this upset you.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
menEnts: [[['Adela Quested'], ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested']]]

qText:
But let us discuss things; it's all so
frightfully important, we mustn't make false steps. I want next to
hear your point of view about me   it might help us both.
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested'], ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested'], ['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested']]]

qText:
I don't much believe in this
discussing   besides, I'm so dead with all this extra work Mohurram's
bringing, if you'll excuse me.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
I only want everything to be absolutely clear between us, and to
answer any questions you care to put to me on my conduct.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
But I haven't got any questions. You've acted within your rights,
you were quite right to come out and have a look at me doing my
work, it was an excellent plan, and anyhow it's no use talking
further   we should only get up steam.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
I suppose that there is nothing else; it's unpardonable of me to
have given you and your mother all this bother,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Yes, nothing else,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
We've been awfully British over it, but
I suppose that's all right.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: As we are British, I suppose it is.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Anyhow we've not quarrelled, Ronny.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Oh, that would have been too absurd. Why should we quarrel?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: I think we shall keep friends.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: I know we shall.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Quite so.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Do you know what the name
of that green bird up above us is?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Bee-eater.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Oh no, Ronny, it has red bars on its wings.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Parrot,
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Good gracious no.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: McBryde has an illustrated bird book,
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
I'm
no good at all at birds, in fact I'm useless at any information
outside my own job. It's a great pity.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: So am I. I'm useless at everything.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: What do I hear?
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText:
What most improbable
statement have I heard? An English lady useless? No, no, no, no,
no.
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText: Hallo, Nawab Bahadur! Been watching the polo again?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: I have, sahib, I have.
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText: How do you do?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Would half an hour's spin entertain you at
all?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Oughtn't we to get back to the bungalow.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Why?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
I think perhaps I ought to see your mother and discuss future
plans.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: That's as you like, but there's no hurry, is there?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Let me take you to the bungalow, and first the little spin,
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText:
He may show you some aspect of the country I can't, and he's a
real loyalist. I thought you might care for a bit of a change.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
menEnts: [[['The Nawab Badahur'], ['Adela Quested'], ['The Nawab Badahur'], ['Adela Quested']]]

qText:
Despite my
advanced years, I am learning to drive,
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText:
Man can learn
everything if he will but try.
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText:
I do not do the actual steering. I sit and ask my
chauffeur questions, and thus learn the reason for everything that
is done before I do it myself. By this method serious and I may
say ludicrous accidents, such as befell one of my compatriots
during that delightful reception at the English Club, are avoided.
Our good Panna Lal! I hope, sahib, that great damage was not done
to your flowers. Let us have our little spin down the Gangavati
road. Half one league onwards!
speaker: The Nawab Badahur
menEnts: [[['Dr. Panna Lal'], ['Dr. Panna Lal'], ['Dr. Panna Lal']]]

qText: What's the damage?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
You give me five
minutes' time, I'll take you any dam anywhere.
speaker: Mr. Harris
refExp: The Eurasian inclined to be flustered rallied to the sound of his voice and every inch an Englishman replied
menEnts: [[['Adela Quested', 'The Nawab Badahur', 'Ronny Heaslop'], ['Adela Quested', 'The Nawab Badahur', 'Ronny Heaslop']]]

qText: Frightened, Adela?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Not a bit.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: I consider not to be frightened the height of folly,
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText: Well, it's all over now, tears are useless,
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: We had some luck butting that tree.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
All over . . . oh yes, the danger is past, let us smoke cigarettes,
let us do anything we please. Oh yes . . . enjoy ourselves   oh my
merciful God . . .
speaker: The Nawab Badahur
menEnts: [[['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested', 'The Nawab Badahur'], ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested', 'The Nawab Badahur'], ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested', 'The Nawab Badahur']]]

qText: Wasn't the bridge. We skidded.
