speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: We didn't skid,
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested', 'The Nawab Badahur']], [['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested', 'The Nawab Badahur']]]

qText:
We ran into
an animal.
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested', 'The Nawab Badahur']], [['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested', 'The Nawab Badahur']]]

qText: An animal?
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText: A large animal rushed up out of the dark on the right and hit us.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: By Jove, she's right,
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: The paint's gone.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: By Jove, sir, your lady is right,
speaker: Mr. Harris

qText: Of course I'm right. I saw its hairy back quite plainly.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: I say, Adela, what was it?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
I don't know the animals any better than the birds here   too big
for a goat.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Exactly, too big for a goat . . .
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText: Let's go into this; let's look for its tracks.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
menEnts: [[['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested', 'The Nawab Badahur'], ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested', 'The Nawab Badahur']]]

qText: Exactly; you wish to borrow this electric torch.
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText: I believe it was a buffalo,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Exactly.
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText: Unless it was a hyena.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Excellent, a hyena,
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText: Mr. Harris!
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText: Half a mo-ment. Give me ten minutes' time.
speaker: Mr. Harris

qText: Sahib says hyena.
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText:
Don't worry Mr. Harris. He saved us from a nasty smash. Harris,
well done!
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
menEnts: [[['Mr. Harris'], ['Mr. Harris'], ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested', 'The Nawab Badahur'], ['Mr. Harris']]]

qText:
A smash, sahib, that would not have taken place had he obeyed and
taken us Gangavati side, instead of Marabar.
speaker: The Nawab Badahur
menEnts: [[['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Mr. Harris'], ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested', 'The Nawab Badahur']]]

qText:
My fault that. I told him to come this way because the road's
better. Mr. Lesley has made it pukka right up to the hills.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Ah, now I begin to understand.
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText: Not at all,
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
Mr. Heaslop, Miss Quested, what are you holding up an innocent
female for?
speaker: Miss Derek

qText: We've had a breakdown.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: But how putrid!
speaker: Miss Derek

qText: We ran into a hyena!
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: How absolutely rotten!
speaker: Miss Derek

qText: Can you give us a lift?
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: Yes, indeed.
speaker: Miss Derek

qText: Take me too,
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText: Heh, what about me?
speaker: Mr. Harris

qText: Now what's all this? I'm not an omnibus,
speaker: Miss Derek

qText:
I've a harmonium and two dogs in here with me as it is.
I'll take three of you if one'll sit in front and nurse a pug. No
more.
speaker: Miss Derek

qText: I will sit in front,
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText: Then hop in: I've no notion who you are.
speaker: Miss Derek

qText:
Heh no, what about my dinner? I can't be left alone all the
night.
speaker: Mr. Harris

qText: Nussu will bring you out some suitable dinner upon a bicycle,
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText:
I
shall despatch him with all possible speed. Meanwhile, repair my
car.
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText:
I don't believe in these
people letting you down,
speaker: Miss Derek

qText:
If I didn't snatch like the
devil, I should be nowhere. He doesn't want the car, silly fool!
Surely it's to the credit of his State I should be seen about in
it at Chandrapore during my leave. He ought to look at it that way.
Anyhow he's got to look at it that way. My Maharani's different   my
Maharani's a dear. That's her fox terrier, poor little devil. I
fished them out both with the driver. Imagine taking dogs to a
Chiefs' Conference! As sensible as taking Chiefs, perhaps.
speaker: Miss Derek

qText:
The harmonium   the harmonium's my little
mistake, I own. They rather had me over the harmonium. I meant it
to stop on the train. Oh lor'!
speaker: Miss Derek

qText:
They always sack me before that happens, and then I get another
job. The whole of India seethes with Maharanis and Ranis and Begums
who clamour for such as me.
speaker: Miss Derek

qText: Really. I had no idea.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
How could you have any idea, Mr. Heaslop? What should he know
about Maharanis, Miss Quested? Nothing. At least I should hope
not.
speaker: Miss Derek

qText: I understand those big people are not particularly interesting,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Ah, there you're wrong. They're priceless.
speaker: Miss Derek

qText: I would scarcely call her wrong,
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText:
A Native State, a Hindu State, the wife of a ruler of a Hindu
State, may beyond doubt be a most excellent lady, and let it not
be for a moment supposed that I suggest anything against the
character of Her Highness the Maharani of Mudkul. But I fear she
will be uneducated, I fear she will be superstitious. Indeed, how
could she be otherwise? What opportunity of education has such a
lady had? Oh, superstition is terrible, terrible! oh, it is the
great defect in our Indian character!
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText:
Oh, it is the duty of
each and every citizen to shake superstition off, and though I have
little experience of Hindu States, and none of this particular one,
namely Mudkul (the Ruler, I fancy, has a salute of but eleven
guns)   yet I cannot imagine that they have been as successful as
British India, where we see reason and orderliness spreading in
every direction, like a most health-giving flood!
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText: Golly!
speaker: Miss Derek

qText:
Ronny, I should like to take
back what I said on the Maidan.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Come along and let's tell the mater all this
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
Look here, both of you, see India if you like and as you
like   I know I made myself rather ridiculous at Fielding's, but . . .
it's different now. I wasn't quite sure of myself.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
menEnts: [[['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Cyril Fielding']]]

qText:
My duties here are evidently finished, I don't want to see India
now; now for my passage back,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: What does our old gentleman of the car think?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Our old gentleman is helpful and sound, as he always is over
public affairs. You've seen in him our show Indian.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
menEnts: [[['The Nawab Badahur'], ['The Nawab Badahur'], ['Adela Quested'], ['The Nawab Badahur']]]

qText: Have I really?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
I'm afraid so. Incredible, aren't they, even the best of them?
They're all   they all forget their back collar studs sooner or
later. You've had to do with three sets of Indians to-day, the
Bhattacharyas, Aziz, and this chap, and it really isn't a
coincidence that they've all let you down.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: I like Aziz, Aziz is my real friend,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
When the animal runs into us the Nawab loses his head, deserts
his unfortunate chauffeur, intrudes upon Miss Derek . . . no great
crimes, no great crimes, but no white man would have done it.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
menEnts: [[['The Nawab Badahur', 'Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested'], ['The Nawab Badahur'], ['The Nawab Badahur'], ['The Nawab Badahur'], ['Miss Derek']]]

qText: What animal?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Oh, we had a small accident on the Marabar road. Adela thinks it
was a hyena.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText: An accident?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
Nothing; no one hurt. Our excellent host awoke much rattled from
his dreams, appeared to think it was our fault, and chanted exactly,
exactly.
speaker: Ronny Heaslop
menEnts: [[['The Nawab Badahur'], ['The Nawab Badahur'], ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested']]]

qText: A ghost!
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Yes, nothing criminal,
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
but there's the native,
and there's one of the reasons why we don't admit him to our clubs,
and how a decent girl like Miss Derek can take service under
natives puzzles me. . . . But I must get on with my work. Krishna!
speaker: Ronny Heaslop

qText:
Will you play Patience with your future mother-in-law, dear Adela,
or does it seem too tame?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
I should like to   I don't feel a bit excited   I'm just glad it's
settled up at last, but I'm not conscious of vast changes. We are
all three the same people still.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: That's much the best feeling to have.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: I suppose so,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
I feared at Mr. Fielding's that it might be settled the other way
. . . black knave on a red queen. . . .
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
You heard me tell Aziz and Godbole I wasn't
stopping in their country. I didn't mean it, so why did I say it?
I feel I haven't been   frank enough, attentive enough, or something.
It's as if I got everything out of proportion. You have been so
very good to me, and I meant to be good when I sailed, but somehow
I haven't been. . . . Mrs. Moore, if one isn't absolutely honest,
what is the use of existing?
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[['Mrs. Moore'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Professor Godbole'], ['Professor Godbole', 'Dr. Aziz'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore']]]

qText: I wouldn't worry,
speaker: Mrs. Moore
Mrs. Moore

qText: You mean that my bothers are mixed up with India?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: India's
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: What made you call it a ghost?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Call what a ghost?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
The animal thing that hit us. Didn't you say    Oh, a ghost,' in
passing.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: I couldn't have been thinking of what I was saying.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: It was probably a hyena, as a matter of fact.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Ah, very likely.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
If I had been killed, what
matter? it must happen sometime; but they who trusted me
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText:
You know,
Nureddin,
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText:
you know, my
dear fellow, we Moslems simply must get rid of these superstitions,
or India will never advance. How long must I hear of the savage
pig upon the Marabar Road?
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText:
Your grandfather belongs to another generation, and I respect and
love the old gentleman, as you know. I say nothing against him,
only that it is wrong for us, because we are young. I want you to
promise me   Nureddin, are you listening?   not to believe in Evil
Spirits, and if I die (for my health grows very weak) to bring up
my three children to disbelieve in them too.
speaker: The Nawab Badahur

qText: Red ten on a black knave,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: No Englishman understands us except Mr. Fielding,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
but how shall I see him again? If he entered this room
the disgrace of it would kill me.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
That's
India all over . . . how like us . . . there we are . . .
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Hassan!
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Look at those flies, brother;
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Huzoor, those are flies.
speaker: Hassan

qText: Good, good, they are, excellent, but why have I called you?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: To drive them elsewhere,
speaker: Hassan

qText: Driven elsewhere, they always return.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Huzoor.
speaker: Hassan

qText:
You must make some arrangement against flies; that is why you are
my servant,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Good, very good. Now what have you to do?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Kill flies.
speaker: Hassan

qText: Good. Do it.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Aziz, my dear fellow, we are greatly concerned,
speaker: Hamidullah

qText: When a doctor falls ill it is a serious matter,
speaker: Syed Mohammed
refExp: said the voice of Mr Syed Mohammed

qText: When an engineer falls ill, it is equally important,
speaker: Mr. Haq
refExp: said the voice of Mr Haq

qText: Oh yes, we are all jolly important, our salaries prove it.
speaker: Syed Mohammed

qText: Dr. Aziz took tea with our Principal last Thursday afternoon,
speaker: Rafi

qText:
Professor Godbole, who also
attended, has sickened too, which seems rather a curious thing,
sir, does it not?
speaker: Rafi

qText: Humbug!
speaker: Hamidullah

qText: Humbug, most certainly,
speaker: _group

qText: Is Professor Godbole ill?
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menTexts: [['Professor Godbole'], [], ['you', 'Mr. Syed Mohammed', 'Mr. Haq', 'you', 'you', 'Hamidullah', 'you', 'him', 'the excellent fellow']]
menEnts: [[['Professor Godbole']], [], [['Syed Mohammed'], ['Syed Mohammed'], ['Mr. Haq'], ['Mr. Haq'], ['Hamidullah'], ['Hamidullah'], ['Hamidullah'], ['Professor Godbole'], ['Professor Godbole']]]

qText: I am sincerely sorry.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menTexts: [['Professor Godbole'], [], ['you', 'Mr. Syed Mohammed', 'Mr. Haq', 'you', 'you', 'Hamidullah', 'you', 'him', 'the excellent fellow']]
menEnts: [[['Professor Godbole']], [], [['Syed Mohammed'], ['Syed Mohammed'], ['Mr. Haq'], ['Mr. Haq'], ['Hamidullah'], ['Hamidullah'], ['Hamidullah'], ['Professor Godbole'], ['Professor Godbole']]]

qText:
How do you
do, Mr. Syed Mohammed, Mr. Haq? How very kind of you to enquire
after my health! How do you do, Hamidullah? But you bring me bad
news. What is wrong with him, the excellent fellow?
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menTexts: [['Professor Godbole'], [], ['you', 'Mr. Syed Mohammed', 'Mr. Haq', 'you', 'you', 'Hamidullah', 'you', 'him', 'the excellent fellow']]
menEnts: [[['Professor Godbole']], [], [['Syed Mohammed'], ['Syed Mohammed'], ['Mr. Haq'], ['Mr. Haq'], ['Hamidullah'], ['Hamidullah'], ['Hamidullah'], ['Professor Godbole'], ['Professor Godbole']]]

qText: Why don't you answer, Rafi? You're the great authority,
speaker: Syed Mohammed

qText: Yes, Rafi's the great man,
speaker: Hamidullah

qText:
Rafi
is the Sherlock Holmes of Chandrapore. Speak up, Rafi.
speaker: Hamidullah

qText: Diarrh  a,
speaker: Rafi

qText:
If this is so, this is a very serious thing: this is scarcely the
end of March. Why have I not been informed?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Dr. Panna Lal attends him, sir.
speaker: Rafi

qText:
Oh yes, both Hindus; there we have it; they hang together like
flies and keep everything dark. Rafi, come here. Sit down. Tell me
all the details. Is there vomiting also?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Oh yes indeed, sir, and the serious pains.
speaker: Rafi

qText: That settles it. In twenty-four hours he will be dead.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: All illness proceeds from Hindus,
speaker: Mr. Haq

qText:
That is exactly my
own view.
speaker: Syed Mohammed

qText:
Aziz,
Aziz, my dear boy, we must be going, we are already late. Get well
quickly, for I do not know what our little circle would do without
you.
speaker: Mr. Haq
menEnts: [[['Dr. Aziz'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah'], ['Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah'], ['Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah', 'Mr. Haq', 'Dr. Aziz'], ['Dr. Aziz']]]

qText: I shall not forget those affectionate words,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Add mine to them,
speaker: Syed Mohammed

qText: Thank you, Mr. Syed Mohammed, I will.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: And mine,
speaker: Hamidullah

qText: And, sir, accept mine,
speaker: Rafi

qText:
Gentlemen, you will excuse, I have come to enquire by Major
Callendar's orders,
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText: Here he lies,
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText: Dr. Aziz, Dr, Aziz, I come to enquire.
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText: Your hand also, please.
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal
refExp: He took it gazed at the flies on the ceiling and finally announced

qText: Some temperature.
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal
refExp: He took it gazed at the flies on the ceiling and finally announced

qText: I think not much,
speaker: Ram Chand

qText: Some; he should remain in bed,
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText:
How is
stomach?
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText: how head?
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText:
This is a great relief to us, it is very good of you to call,
Doctor Sahib,
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']
menEnts: [[['Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah'], ['Dr. Panna Lal'], ['Dr. Panna Lal']]]

qText: It is only my duty.
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText: We know how busy you are.
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText: Yes, that is true.
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText: And how much illness there is in the city.
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText: There is always illness,
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText:
and I am
always busy   it is a doctor's nature.
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText:
He has not a minute, he is due double sharp at Government College
now,
speaker: Ram Chand

qText: You attend Professor Godbole there perhaps?
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText: We hope his diarrh  a is ceasing.
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText: He progresses, but not from diarrh  a.
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText:
We are in some anxiety over him   he and Dr. Aziz are great friends.
If you could tell us the name of his complaint we should be grateful
to you.
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']
menEnts: [[['Dr. Aziz', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah'], ['Professor Godbole'], ['Professor Godbole'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Dr. Panna Lal'], ['Dr. Aziz', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah'], ['Professor Godbole'], ['Dr. Aziz', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah'], ['Dr. Panna Lal']]]

qText: H  morrhoids.
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText: And so much, my dear Rafi, for your cholera,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Cholera, cholera, what next, what now?
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText: Who spreads such untrue reports about my patients?
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText:
I hear cholera, I hear bubonic plague, I hear every species of
lie. Where will it end, I ask myself sometimes. This city is full
of misstatements, and the originators of them ought to be discovered
and punished authoritatively.
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText:
Rafi, do you hear that? Now why do you stuff us up with all this
humbug?
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText: That is no reason you should bring a charge against a doctor,
speaker: Ram Chand

qText: Exactly, exactly,
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText:
You must
apologize properly, Rafi, I can see your uncle wishes it,
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText:
You have not yet said that you are sorry for the trouble you have
caused this gentleman by your carelessness.
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText: It is only a boy,
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText: Even boys must learn,
speaker: Ram Chand

qText: Your own son failing to pass the lowest standard, I think,
speaker: Syed Mohammed

qText:
Oh, indeed? Oh yes, perhaps. He has not the advantage of a relative
in the Prosperity Printing Press.
speaker: Ram Chand

qText:
Nor you the advantage of conducting their cases in the Courts any
longer.
speaker: Syed Mohammed

qText:
I say!
Is he ill or isn't he ill?
speaker: _unknowable
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: Sit down,
speaker: Dr. Aziz
addressee: ['Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: It is good of Mr. Fielding to condescend to visit our friend,
speaker: Mr. Haq
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: We are touched by this great kindness.
speaker: Mr. Haq
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText:
Don't talk to him like that, he doesn't want it, and he doesn't
want three chairs; he's not three Englishmen,
speaker: Dr. Aziz
addressee: ['Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText:
Rafi,
come here. Sit down again. I'm delighted you could come with Mr.
Hamidullah, my dear boy; it will help me to recover, seeing you.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
addressee: ['Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: Forgive my mistakes,
speaker: Rafi
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Hamidullah']

qText: Well, are you ill, Aziz, or aren't you?
speaker: Cyril Fielding
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: No doubt Major Callendar has told you that I am shamming.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
addressee: ['Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: Well, are you?
speaker: Cyril Fielding
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: Enquire from Dr. Panna Lal.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
addressee: ['Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: You're sure I don't tire you by stopping?
speaker: Cyril Fielding
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText:
Why, no! There are six people present in my small room already.
Please remain seated, if you will excuse the informality.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
addressee: ['Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: He is ill and he is not ill,
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText: And I suppose that most of us are in that same case.
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText:
The whole world looks to be dying, still it doesn't die, so we
must assume the existence of a beneficent Providence.
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText: Oh, that is true, how true!
speaker: Mr. Haq
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: Does Mr. Fielding think it's true?.
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText: Think which true? The world isn't dying. I'm certain of that!
speaker: Cyril Fielding
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: No, no   the existence of Providence.
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText: Well, I don't believe in Providence.
speaker: Cyril Fielding
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: But how then can you believe in God?
speaker: Syed Mohammed
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: I don't believe in God.
speaker: Cyril Fielding
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText:
Is it correct that
most are atheists in England now?
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText:
The educated thoughtful people? I should say so, though they don't
like the name. The truth is that the West doesn't bother much over
belief and disbelief in these days. Fifty years ago, or even when
you and I were young, much more fuss was made.
speaker: Cyril Fielding
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: And does not morality also decline?
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText:
It depends what you call   yes, yes, I suppose morality does
decline.
speaker: Cyril Fielding
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText:
Excuse the question, but if this is the case, how is England
justified in holding India?
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText:
It's a question I can't get my
mind on to,
speaker: Cyril Fielding
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText:
I'm out here personally because I needed
a job. I cannot tell you why England is here or whether she ought
to be here. It's beyond me.
speaker: Cyril Fielding
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: Well-qualified Indians also need jobs in the educational.
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText: I guess they do; I got in first,
speaker: Cyril Fielding
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText:
Then excuse me again   is it fair an Englishman should occupy one
when Indians are available? Of course I mean nothing personally.
Personally we are delighted you should be here, and we benefit
greatly by this frank talk.
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']
menEnts: [[['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Hamidullah'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Hamidullah']]]

qText:
I'm delighted
to be here too   that's my answer, there's my only excuse. I can't
tell you anything about fairness. It mayn't have been fair I should
have been born. I take up some other fellow's air, don't I, whenever
I breathe? Still, I'm glad it's happened, and I'm glad I'm out
here. However big a badmash one is   if one's happy in consequence,
that is some justification.
speaker: Cyril Fielding
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText:
And those Englishmen who are not delighted
to be in India   have they no excuse?
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText: None. Chuck 'em out.
speaker: Cyril Fielding
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: It may be difficult to separate them from the rest,
speaker: Hamidullah
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi']

qText: Worse than difficult, wrong,
speaker: Ram Chand
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText:
No Indian
gentleman approves chucking out as a proper thing. Here we differ
from those other nations. We are so spiritual.
speaker: Ram Chand
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: Oh that is true, how true!
speaker: Mr. Haq
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText:
Is it true, Mr. Haq? I don't consider us spiritual. We can't
co-ordinate, we can't co-ordinate, it only comes to that. We can't
keep engagements, we can't catch trains. What more than this is
the so-called spirituality of India? You and I ought to be at the
Committee of Notables, we're not; our friend Dr. Lal ought to be
with his patients, he isn't. So we go on, and so we shall continue
to go, I think, until the end of time.
speaker: Ram Chand
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']
menEnts: [[['Mr. Haq'], ['Mr. Haq'], ['Mr. Haq', 'Ram Chand'], ['Dr. Panna Lal'], ['Dr. Panna Lal'], ['Dr. Panna Lal']]]

qText: It is not the end of time, it is scarcely ten-thirty, ha, ha!
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal
menEnts: [[], [['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding']]]

qText:
Gentlemen,
if I may be allowed to say a few words, what an interesting talk,
also thankfulness and gratitude to Mr. Fielding in the first place
teaches our sons and gives them all the great benefits of his
experience and judgment
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal
menEnts: [[], [['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding']]]

qText: Dr. Lal!
speaker: Dr. Aziz
addressee: ['Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: Dr. Aziz?
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText: You sit on my leg.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
addressee: ['Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: I beg pardon, but some might say your leg kicks.
speaker: Dr. Panna Lal

qText: Come along, we tire the invalid in either case,
speaker: Cyril Fielding
addressee: ['Dr. Aziz', 'Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Hassan', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']
menEnts: [[['Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah'], ['Dr. Aziz']]]

qText:
Aziz has a high opinion of you, he only did not speak because of
his illness.
speaker: _unknowable
addressee: ['Ram Chand', 'Dr. Panna Lal', 'Cyril Fielding', 'Mr. Haq', 'Syed Mohammed', 'Rafi', 'Hamidullah']

qText: I quite understand,
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Here's your home,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Here's the celebrated hospitality of the East. Look
at the flies. Look at the chunam coming off the walls. Isn't it
jolly? Now I suppose you want to be off, having seen an Oriental
interior.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Anyhow, you want to rest.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
I can rest the whole day, thanks to worthy Dr. Lal. Major
Callendar's spy, I suppose you know, but this time it didn't work.
I am allowed to have a slight temperature.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Callendar doesn't trust anyone, English or Indian: that's his
character, and I wish you weren't under him; but you are, and
that's that.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
Before you go, for you are evidently in a great hurry, will you
please unlock that drawer? Do you see a piece of brown paper at
the top?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Yes.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Open it.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Who is this?
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
She was my wife. You are the first Englishman she has ever come
before. Now put her photograph away.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Really, I don't know why you pay me this great
compliment, Aziz, but I do appreciate it.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
Oh, it's nothing, she was not a highly educated woman or even
beautiful, but put it away. You would have seen her, so why should
you not see her photograph?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: You would have allowed me to see her?
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
Why not? I believe in the purdah, but I should have told her you
were my brother, and she would have seen you. Hamidullah saw her,
and several others.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Did she think they were your brothers?
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
Of course not, but the word exists and is convenient. All men are
my brothers, and as soon as one behaves as such he may see my
wife.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
And when the whole world behaves as such, there will be no more
purdah?
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
It is because you can say and feel such a remark as that, that I
show you the photograph,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
It is beyond the power of most men. It is because you behave well
while I behave badly that I show it you. I never expected you to
come back just now when I called you. I thought,
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding']], [['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding']]]

qText:
Mr. Fielding, no one can ever
realize how much kindness we Indians need, we do not even realize
it ourselves. But we know when it has been given. We do not forget,
though we may seem to. Kindness, more kindness, and even after that
more kindness. I assure you it is the only hope.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding']], [['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding']]]

qText:
We can't build up India except on what we feel.
What is the use of all these reforms, and Conciliation Committees
for Mohurram, and shall we cut the tazia short or shall we carry
it another route, and Councils of Notables and official parties
where the English sneer at our skins?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
It's beginning at the wrong end, isn't it? I know, but institutions
and the governments don't.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Put her away, she is of no importance, she is dead,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
I showed her to you because I have nothing else to show.
You may look round the whole of my bungalow now, and empty
everything. I have no other secrets, my three children live away
with their grandmamma, and that is all.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I shall not really be intimate with this fellow,
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: nor with anyone.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: How did you like the two ladies you met last Thursday?
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: How do you like Englishwomen generally?
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
Hamidullah liked them in England. Here we never look at them. Oh
no, much too careful. Let's talk of something else.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Hamidullah's right: they are much nicer in England. There's
something that doesn't suit them out here.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Why are you not married?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Because I have more or
less come through without it,
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
I was thinking of telling you a little about myself some day if
I can make it interesting enough. The lady I liked wouldn't marry
me   that is the main point, but that's fifteen years ago and now
means nothing.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: But you haven't children.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: None.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Excuse the following question: have you any illegitimate children?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: No. I'd willingly tell you if I had.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Then your name will entirely die out.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: It must.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Well.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
This indifference is what the Oriental
will never understand.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I don't care for children.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Caring has nothing to do with it,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
I don't feel their absence, I don't want them weeping around my
death-bed and being polite about me afterwards, which I believe is
the general notion. I'd far rather leave a thought behind me than
a child. Other people can have children. No obligation, with
England getting so chock-a-block and overrunning India for jobs.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Why don't you marry Miss Quested?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Good God! why, the girl's a prig.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Prig, prig? Kindly explain. Isn't that a bad word?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Oh, I don't know her, but she struck me as one of the more pathetic
products of Western education. She depresses me.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: But prig, Mr. Fielding? How's that?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
She goes on and on as if she's at a lecture   trying ever so hard
to understand India and life, and occasionally taking a note.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: I thought her so nice and sincere.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: So she probably is,
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
But I can't
marry her if I wanted to, for she has just become engaged to the
City Magistrate.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Has she indeed? I am so glad!
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
It's the old mother's doing. She was afraid her dear boy would
choose for himself, so she brought out the girl on purpose, and
flung them together until it happened.
speaker: Cyril Fielding
menEnts: [[['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested']]]

qText: Mrs. Moore did not mention that to me among her plans.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
I may have got it wrong   I'm out of club gossip. But anyhow they're
engaged to be married.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Yes, you're out of it, my poor chap,
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding']], [['Adela Quested'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Cyril Fielding']]]

qText:
No Miss Quested
for Mr. Fielding. However, she was not beautiful. She has
practically no breasts, if you come to think of it.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding']], [['Adela Quested'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Cyril Fielding']]]

qText:
For the City Magistrate they shall be sufficient perhaps, and he
for her. For you I shall arrange a lady with breasts like mangoes.
. . .
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: No, you won't.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
I will not really, and besides your position makes it dangerous
for you.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
You can't be
too careful in every way, Mr. Fielding; whatever you say or do in
this damned country there is always some envious fellow on the
look-out. You may be surprised to know that there were at least
three spies sitting here when you came to enquire. I was really a
good deal upset that you talked in that fashion about God. They
will certainly report it.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Cyril Fielding']]]

qText: To whom?
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
That's all very well, but you spoke against morality also, and
you said you had come to take other people's jobs. All that was
very unwise. This is an awful place for scandal. Why, actually one
of your own pupils was listening.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Thanks for telling me that; yes, I must try and be more careful.
If I'm interested, I'm apt to forget myself. Still, it doesn't do
real harm.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: But speaking out may get you into trouble.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: It's often done so in the past.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
There, listen to that! But the end of it might be that you lost
your job.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: If I do, I do. I shall survive it. I travel light.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Travel light! You are a most extraordinary race,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Is it your climate, or what?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Plenty of Indians travel light too   saddhus and such. It's one of
the things I admire about your country. Any man can travel light
until he has a wife or children. That's part of my case against
marriage. I'm a holy man minus the holiness. Hand that on to your
three spies, and tell them to put it in their pipes.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
I can't be sacked from my job, because my job's Education. I
believe in teaching people to be individuals, and to understand
other individuals. It's the only thing I do believe in. At
Government College, I mix it up with trigonometry, and so on. When
I'm a saddhu, I shall mix it up with something else.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
You might tell your servant to bring my horse. He doesn't seem to
appreciate my Urdu.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText:
I know. I gave him orders not to. Such are the tricks we play on
unfortunate Englishmen. Poor Mr. Fielding! But I will release you
now. Oh dear! With the exception of yourself and Hamidullah, I have
no one to talk to in this place. You like Hamidullah, don't you?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Very much.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Do you promise to come at once to us when you are in trouble?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I never can be in trouble.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: There goes a queer chap, I trust he won't come to grief,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
But
you've come, after all. Oh how very very kind of you!
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: This is the happiest moment in all my life.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
You don't require tickets   please stop your servant. There are no
tickets on the Marabar branch line; it is its peculiarity. You come
to the carriage and rest till Mr. Fielding joins us. Did you know
you are to travel purdah? Will you like that?
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Cyril Fielding'], ['Adela Quested', 'Dr. Aziz', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore']]]

qText: Send back your servant,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
He is unnecessary. Then
we shall all be Moslems together.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
And he is such a horrible servant. Antony, you can go; we don't
want you,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Master told me to come.
speaker: Antony

qText: Mistress tells you to go.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Master says, keep near the ladies all the morning.
speaker: Antony

qText: Well, your ladies won't have you.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Do
get rid of him, Dr. Aziz!
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Mohammed Latif!
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Here is my cousin, Mr. Mohammed Latif. Oh no, don't shake hands.
He is an Indian of the old-fashioned sort, he prefers to salaam.
There, I told you so. Mohammed Latif, how beautifully you salaam.
See, he hasn't understood; he knows no English.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Mohammed Latif'], ['Mohammed Latif'], ['Mohammed Latif'], ['Mohammed Latif'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Mohammed Latif'], ['Mohammed Latif'], ['Mohammed Latif']]]

qText: You spick lie,
speaker: Mohammed Latif

qText:
I spick a lie! Oh, jolly good. Isn't he a funny old man? We will
have great jokes with him later. He does all sorts of little
things. He is not nearly as stupid as you think, and awfully poor.
It's lucky ours is a large family.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Mohammed Latif'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore', 'Dr. Aziz'], ['Mohammed Latif'], ['Mohammed Latif'], ['Mohammed Latif'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore']]]

qText:
But you get inside, make yourselves at home; yes,
you lie down.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Excuse me, now I must meet our other two guests!
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Tell me another time, brother, when I have more leisure, for now,
as I have already explained, we have to give pleasure to non-Moslems.
Three will be Europeans, one a Hindu, which must not be forgotten.
Every attention must be paid to Professor Godbole, lest he feel
that he is inferior to my other guests.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Mohammed Latif'], ['Mohammed Latif', 'Dr. Aziz'], ['Professor Godbole'], ['Professor Godbole'], ['Professor Godbole'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore']]]

qText: I will discuss philosophy with him.
speaker: Mohammed Latif

qText:
That will be kind of you; but the servants are even more important.
We must not convey an impression of disorganization. It can be
done, and I expect you to do it . . .
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Merciful God!
speaker: Mohammed Latif

qText: We're monkeys, don't worry,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Mr. Fielding!
Mr. Fielding!
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Bad, bad, you have destroyed me.
speaker: _unknowable
addressee: ['Cyril Fielding', 'Mohammed Latif', 'Dr. Aziz', 'Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore', 'Professor Godbole']

qText: Godbole's pujah did it,
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Jump on, I must have you,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Right, give a hand.
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: He's not to, he'll kill himself,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: I'm all right, you're all right, don't worry,
speaker: Cyril Fielding
refExp: He scrambled on to his feet and bawled

qText: Mrs. Moore, Miss Quested, our expedition is a ruin.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Get in, get in; you'll kill yourself as well as Mr. Fielding. I
see no ruin.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: How is that? Oh, explain to me!
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: We shall be all Moslems together now, as you promised.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Get in, Dr. Aziz, you make us giddy,
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[['Dr. Aziz'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Mrs. Moore', 'Adela Quested']], [['Cyril Fielding', 'Professor Godbole'], ['Cyril Fielding', 'Professor Godbole']]]

qText:
If
they're so foolish as to miss the train, that's their loss, not
ours.
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[['Dr. Aziz'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Mrs. Moore', 'Adela Quested']], [['Cyril Fielding', 'Professor Godbole'], ['Cyril Fielding', 'Professor Godbole']]]

qText: I am to blame. I am the host.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Nonsense, go to your carriage. We're going to have a delightful
time without them.
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[['Dr. Aziz'], ['Adela Quested', 'Dr. Aziz', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Cyril Fielding', 'Professor Godbole']]]

qText:
Mohammed Latif, by the way, what is in these caves, brother? Why
are we all going to see them?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: What a nice cheerful servant! What a relief after Antony!
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: They startle one rather. A strange place to make tea in,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
I want to sack Antony. His behaviour on the platform has decided
me.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Anyhow, we must get a second servant, because at Simla you will
be at the hotel, and I don't think Ronny's Baldeo . . .
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Very well, you get another servant, and I'll keep Antony with me.
I am used to his unappetizing ways. He will see me through the Hot
Weather.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
I don't believe in the Hot Weather. People like Major Callendar
who always talk about it   it's in the hope of making one feel
inexperienced and small, like their everlasting,    I've been twenty
years in this country.'
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
I believe in the Hot Weather, but never did I suppose it would
bottle me up as it will.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: I won't be bottled up,
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[], [['Mrs. Mcbryde'], ['Mrs. Mcbryde'], ['Mrs. Mcbryde'], ['Mr. Mcbryde'], ['Mrs. Mcbryde'], ['Mr. Mcbryde']]]

qText:
I've no patience with
these women here who leave their husbands grilling in the plains.
Mrs. McBryde hasn't stopped down once since she married; she leaves
her quite intelligent husband alone half the year, and then's
surprised she's out of touch with him.
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[], [['Mrs. Mcbryde'], ['Mrs. Mcbryde'], ['Mrs. Mcbryde'], ['Mr. Mcbryde'], ['Mrs. Mcbryde'], ['Mr. Mcbryde']]]

qText: She has children, you see.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Oh yes, that's true,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
It is the children who are the first consideration. Until they
are grown up, and married off. When that happens one has again the
right to live for oneself   in the plains or the hills, as suits.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Oh yes, you're perfectly right. I never thought it out.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: If one has not become too stupid and old.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
My idea now is that my cousins shall find me a servant in Simla,
at all events to see me through the wedding, after which Ronny
means to reorganize his staff entirely. He does it very well for
a bachelor; still, when he is married no doubt various changes will
have to be made   his old servants won't want to take their orders
from me, and I don't blame them.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Anything to be seen of the hills?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Only various shades of the dark.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: We can't be far from the place where my hyena was.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Perhaps this is mine; anyhow, the road runs parallel with
the railway.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
I will fetch you from Simla when it's cool enough. I will unbottle
you in fact,
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore']], [['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested'], ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore']]]

qText:
We then see some of
the Mogul stuff   how appalling if we let you miss the Taj!   and then
I will see you off at Bombay. Your last glimpse of this country
really shall be interesting.
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore']], [['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested'], ['Ronny Heaslop', 'Adela Quested'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore']]]

qText: They're rather wonderful.
speaker: Adela Quested
refExp: Adela had ceased to plan and leant out of a window saying

qText: I'ld not have missed this for anything,
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[], [['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore', 'Adela Quested'], ['Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Turton'], ['Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Turton']]]

qText:
Look, the sun's rising   this'll be absolutely
magnificent   come quickly   look. I wouldn't have missed this for
anything. We should never have seen it if we'd stuck to the Turtons
and their eternal elephants.
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[], [['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore', 'Adela Quested'], ['Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Turton'], ['Mr. Turton', 'Mrs. Turton']]]

qText:
Ah, that must be the false dawn   isn't it caused by dust in the
upper layers of the atmosphere that couldn't fall down during the
night? I think Mr. McBryde said so. Well, I must admit that England
has it as regards sunrises. Do you remember Grasmere?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Ah, dearest Grasmere!
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Good morning, good morning, put on your topis,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Put on your topis at once, the early sun
is highly dangerous for heads. I speak as a doctor.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Good morning, good morning, put on your own.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Not for my thick head,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Nice creature he is,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Listen   Mohammed Latif says    Good morning' next.
speaker: _unknowable

qText:
Dr. Aziz, what's happened to your hills? The train has forgotten
to stop.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Perhaps it is a circular train and goes back to Chandrapore
without a break. Who knows!
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Oh, what a surprise!
speaker: _group

qText:
It takes an hour to get there, an hour to get back, and two hours
for the caves, which we will call three,
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[], [['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore']]]

qText:
The
train back is at eleven-thirty, and you will be sitting down to
your tiffin in Chandrapore with Mr. Heaslop at exactly your usual
hour, namely, one-fifteen. I know everything about you. Four
hours   quite a small expedition   and an hour extra for misfortunes,
which occur somewhat frequently among my people. My idea is to plan
everything without consulting you; but you, Mrs. Moore, or Miss
Quested, you are at any moment to make alterations if you wish,
even if it means giving up the caves. Do you agree? Then mount this
wild animal.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[], [['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Ronny Heaslop'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore']]]

qText: A snake!
speaker: Adela Quested
refExp: Miss Quested saw a thin dark object reared on end at the farther side of a watercourse and said

qText: It isn't a snake.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: A horrid, stuffy place really,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: How quick your servants are!
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
I thought we would eat this before our caves, and breakfast
after.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Isn't this breakfast?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: This breakfast? Did you think I should treat you so strangely?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: How very well it is all arranged.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
That you shall tell me when I return to Chandrapore. Whatever
disgraces I bring upon myself, you remain my guests.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Oh,
what more can I do for her?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Do you ever remember our mosque,
Mrs. Moore?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I do. I do,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: And how rough and rude I was, and how good you were.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: And how happy we both were.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
Friendships last longest that begin like that, I think. Shall I
ever entertain your other children?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Do you know about the others? She will never talk about them to
me,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Ralph and Stella, yes, I know everything about them. But we must
not forget to visit our caves. One of the dreams of my life is
accomplished in having you both here as my guests. You cannot
imagine how you have honoured me. I feel like the Emperor Babur.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore']]]

qText: Why like him?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Because my ancestors came down with him from Afghanistan. They
joined him at Herat. He also had often no more elephants than one,
none sometimes, but he never ceased showing hospitality. When he
fought or hunted or ran away, he would always stop for a time among
hills, just like us; he would never let go of hospitality and
pleasure, and if there was only a little food, he would have it
arranged nicely, and if only one musical instrument, he would
compel it to play a beautiful tune. I take him as my ideal. He is
the poor gentleman, and he became a great king.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
I thought another Emperor is your favourite   I forget the name   you
mentioned him at Mr. Fielding's: what my book calls Aurangzebe.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Alamgir? Oh yes, he was of course the more pious. But Babur   never
in his whole life did he betray a friend, so I can only think of
him this morning. And you know how he died? He laid down his life
for his son. A death far more difficult than battle. They were
caught in the heat. They should have gone back to Kabul for the
bad weather, but could not for reasons of state, and at Agra
Humayun fell sick. Babur walked round the bed three times, and
said,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
and he did bear it away; the fever
left his son and came to him instead, and he died. That is why I
prefer Babur to Alamgir. I ought not to do so, but I do. However,
I mustn't delay you. I see you are ready to start.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Not at all,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
We enjoy
talk like this very much.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
I always enjoy conversing about the Moguls. It is the chief
pleasure I know. You see, those first six emperors were all most
wonderful men, and as soon as one of them is mentioned, no matter
which, I forget everything else in the world except the other five.
You could not find six such kings in all the countries of the
earth, not, I mean, coming one after the other   father, son.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Tell us something about Akbar.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Ah, you have heard the name of Akbar. Good. Hamidullah   whom you
shall meet   will tell you that Akbar is the greatest of all. I say,
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Mrs. Moore']]]

qText: which makes Hamidullah cry,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
But Babur always repented afterwards, which makes the entire
difference, and Akbar never repented of the new religion he invented
instead of the Holy Koran.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
But wasn't Akbar's new religion very fine? It was to embrace the
whole of India.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Miss Quested, fine but foolish. You keep your religion, I mine.
That is the best. Nothing embraces the whole of India, nothing,
nothing, and that was Akbar's mistake.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Oh, do you feel that, Dr. Aziz?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
I hope
you're not right. There will have to be something universal in this
country   I don't say religion, for I'm not religious, but something,
or how else are barriers to be broken down?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Take my own case,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
I don't know whether you happen to have heard,
but I'm going to marry Mr. Heaslop.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: On which my heartiest congratulations.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Mrs. Moore, may I put our difficulty to Dr. Aziz   I mean our
Anglo-Indian one?
speaker: Adela Quested
menEnts: [[['Mrs. Moore'], ['Mrs. Moore', 'Adela Quested'], ['Dr. Aziz'], ['Mrs. Moore', 'Adela Quested']]]

qText: It is your difficulty, not mine, my dear.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
Ah, that's true. Well, by marrying Mr. Heaslop, I shall become
what is known as an Anglo-Indian.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Impossible. Take back such a
terrible remark.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
But I shall; it's inevitable. I can't avoid the label. What I do
hope to avoid is the mentality. Women like
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Some women are so   well,
ungenerous and snobby about Indians, and I should feel too ashamed
for words if I turned like them, but   and here's my difficulty   there's
nothing special about me, nothing specially good or strong, which
will help me to resist my environment and avoid becoming like them.
I've most lamentable defects. That's why I want Akbar's    universal
religion' or the equivalent to keep me decent and sensible. Do you
see what I mean?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
You are certain to be happy with any relative
of Mrs. Moore's,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Oh, my happiness   that's quite another problem. I want to consult
you about this Anglo-Indian difficulty. Can you give me any advice?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
You are absolutely unlike the others, I assure you. You will never
be rude to my people.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I am told we all get rude after a year.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Then you are told a lie,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Come along,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Did you see the reflection of his match   rather pretty?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: I forget . . .
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: But he says this isn't a good cave, the best are on the Kawa Dol.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: I don't think I shall go on to there. I dislike climbing.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
Very well, let's sit down again in the shade until breakfast's
ready.
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Ah, but that'll disappoint him so; he has taken such trouble. You
should go on; you don't mind.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Perhaps I ought to,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText:
Certainly, Miss Quested, so you and I will go together, and leave
Mrs. Moore here, and we will not be long, yet we will not hurry,
because we know that will be her wish.
speaker: Dr. Aziz
menEnts: [[['Adela Quested'], ['Adela Quested'], ['Mrs. Moore'], ['Adela Quested', 'Dr. Aziz'], ['Adela Quested', 'Dr. Aziz'], ['Adela Quested', 'Dr. Aziz'], ['Mrs. Moore']]]

qText: Quite right. I'm sorry not to come too, but I'm a poor walker.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
Dear Mrs. Moore, what does anything matter so long as you are my
guests? I am very glad you are _not_ coming, which sounds strange,
but you are treating me with true frankness, as a friend.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Yes, I am your friend,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
So may I
make another suggestion? Don't let so many people come with you
this time. I think you may find it more convenient.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Exactly, exactly,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Is that all right?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Quite right, now enjoy yourselves, and when you come back tell me
all about it.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: I am going to be ill,
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText:
pretty sure they should come on some
interesting old carvings soon,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: What about love?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Do I take you too fast?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
No, I'm all right,
thanks,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Are you married, Dr. Aziz?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Yes, indeed, do come and see my wife
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Thank you,
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: She is not in Chandrapore just now.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: And have you children?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Yes, indeed, three,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Are they a great pleasure to you?
speaker: Adela Quested

qText: Why, naturally, I adore them,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: I suppose so.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Have you one wife or more than one?
speaker: Adela Quested
refExp: she gave rein to the subject of marriage and said

qText: One, one in my own particular case,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Damn the English even at their
best,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: sight-seeing bores me,
speaker: Adela Quested
refExp: she also went into a cave thinking

qText: Which cave?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: You should have kept her in sight, it was your duty,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Here are twelve caves at least. How am I to know which
contains my guest? Which is the cave I was in myself?
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Merciful Heavens, Miss
Quested is lost,
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Shout!
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Come here!
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
This is the end of my career, my guest is
lost.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Fielding! Oh, I have so wanted you!
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText:
Why haven't you gone
to the Marabar?
speaker: Miss Derek

speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Certainly not.
speaker: Dr. Aziz

qText: Mr. Fielding!
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Good morning again!
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: Mr. Fielding, have you seen Miss Quested?
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: But I've only just arrived. Where is she?
speaker: Cyril Fielding

qText: I do not know.
speaker: Mrs. Moore

qText: Aziz! Where have you put Miss Quested to?
